<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Weapons Sold to Greece, Turkey Transferred to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The United States sold weapons
to Greece and Turkey, and they in turn transferred them to their
respective allies on Cyprus in an effort to outpower each other on
the divided island, the State Department admitted on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Both Greece and Turkey sent U.S.-origin military items to
Cyprus in contravention of the commitments they made to the United
States," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said he was unable to identify the types of weaponry
involved.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has had to make an investigation
into the matter since May 1998 and submitted a classified report
to Congress last Friday.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the investigation, "we have asked Greece and
Turkey to withdraw certain U.S.-origin equipment from Cyprus,"
Rubin said. "Both governments agreed to do so and have informed us
that the items of concern have been removed."
</P>
<P>
The United States often sold weaponry to feuding countries to
make big profit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
