<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Early Resumption of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
Monday called on Israel to resume peace talks with the
Palestinians as soon as possible to pave the way for the final
status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal during his meeting with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, who arrived in Amman Monday afternoon for a two-day
working visit.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also urged the Jewish state to comply with all
agreements it signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian monarch reiterated Jordan's full support to all
the legitimate rights of the Palestinian people, including the
establishment of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Arafat was expected to brief Abdullah and
Jordanian officials on the latest development of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process following the May 17 Israeli
elections, which brought down the hard-line Likud government.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has repeatedly called on Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak to resume peace talks on all tracks, including the
suspended talks with Syria, Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel's peace talks with Arab neighbors remained virtually
deadlocked since 1996 when Benjamin Netanyahu of the Likud party
was elected prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
