<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Probe Sales of Government Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerians inaugurated Monday a
seven- member panel headed by a retired military officer to
investigate the sale of government property during the last 15
years of military rule.
</P>
<P>
The panel was set up following reports that most government
property in Lagos, the west Africa country's commercial capital,
and some state capitals, were sold to military officers or their
cronies.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo said at its inauguration that the
panel would identify all government landed property and those "in
danger of being illegally disposed of."
</P>
<P>
The panel would also review the landed properties of such
government agencies as the ports authority, the national airline
and the railways, three organizations whose properties were
allegedly sold.
</P>
<P>
The panel led by retired Brigadier Gen. Oluwole Rotimi would
also determine the method of disposal of such property and which
kinds of procedures should be followed to punish such illegal
sales.
</P>
<P>
During the nine-month of its sitting, the panel would recommend
 punishment for public officers involved in such illegal disposal
of government assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
