<HEADLINE> Tanzania Fires 120 Cops for Taking Bribes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian police force
has fired over 120 policemen since January 1998 for taking bribes,
a senior police officer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Closing a three-month training course at the a police college
in Zanzibar, Adadi Rajabu, director of Criminal Investigation,
said the policemen's inappropriate behavior of soliciting and
receiving bribes has tarnished the image of Tanzanian police
force.
</P>
<P>
Rajabu, who attended the ceremony on behalf of Tanzania's
General Inspector of Police Omari Mahita, promoted 115 police
constables to the rank of corporal as they have successfully
completed the course, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Although the police force has been mentioned by the 1997
Warioba Corruption Report as one of the bribery taking state
organs, Rajabu said, police should work hard to win people's
trust.
</P>
<P>
Apart from dismissing these 120 policemen, the police has also
transferred 132 officers from one section to another within the
police force, including 89 from the highly criticized traffic
section and the rest from the Criminal Investigation Department.
</P>
<P>
Recently the Tanzania police force has severely punished eight
officers involved in corruption scandals, including demoting four
of them and suspending the rest from duty, said Rajabu.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Rajabu praised policemen for their dedication
despite difficult working conditions, promising that excellent
police officers who stick to code of conduct and regulations will
be awarded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
