NICOSIA -- Cyprus' government said Monday it will not discuss a
confederate solution to the Cyprus issue, threatening not to
participate in talks with the Turkish side if such a solution is
set as a precondition.
</P>
<P>
Government Spokesman Costas Serezis said the Greek Cypriot
government remains committed to the U.N. resolutions which
stipulate for the setting up of a bizonal, bicommunal federation
in the island. (BC-Cyprus-Confederation-Rejection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi has rejected
recent call of western countries and international organizations
for release of 13 Iranian Jews arrested on espionage charges.
</P>
<P>
"At present they are only suspects and no verdict has been
issued about them, therefore, any call for their release before
completion of judicial proceedings will not at all be acceptable
or justifiable," the Islamic Republic News Agency Monday quoted
him as saying. (BC-Iran-Jews-Rejection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In a most noticeable announcement since he started
forming a new government, Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak
said on Monday he prefers the ultra-Orthodox Shas party to the
right-wing Likud as a coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
After making the announcement at a meeting with representatives
of the left-wing Meretz, which has signed a coalition agreement
with Barak's Labor-led One Israel alliance, Barak informed interim
Likud leader Ariel Sharon of his preference, according to Israeli
television reports. (BC-Israel-Coalition) 
</P>
