<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Prefers Shas to Likud in Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- In a most noticeable
announcement since he started forming a new government, Israeli
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak said on Monday he prefers the
ultra-Orthodox Shas party to the right-wing Likud as a coalition
partner.
</P>
<P>
After making the announcement at a meeting with representatives
of the left-wing Meretz, which has signed a coalition agreement
with Barak's Labor-led One Israel alliance, Barak informed interim
Likud leader Ariel Sharon of his preference, according to Israeli
television reports.
</P>
<P>
The Likud and Shas are the second and the third largest party
in the 120-member parliament after the Labor-led One Israel. In
the May elections, Likud plunged from 32 seats to 19, while Shas
jumped from 10 to 17.
</P>
<P>
With a view to materializing his promise to build a government
as broad-based as possible in order to move forward the peace
process and heal the internal rift in the country, Barak has been
courting various parties in the parliament with a record number of
15 factions.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Shas, a religious party of Jews with Middle
East backgrounds, might agree to join Barak's coalition although
it is unhappy that Barak has granted the portfolio of the interior
ministry to the Russian immigrants' party Yisrael Ba'aliya.
</P>
<P>
Shas has controlled the interior ministry for almost 15 years,
a key position which has helped it develop religious schools and
welfare networks, which in return brought wide support to the
party from low-income Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Yisrael b'Aliya was among the first parties that have signed
coalition agreements with Barak. The other two are the National
Religious Party, champion of Jewish settlements in the West Bank,
and Meretz.
</P>
<P>
But Meretz has to decide if it stays in the coalition after
Barak picked Shas as a ruling partner. The party has been strongly
opposed to sitting in the same government with Shas, which it
accuses of ignoring the rule of law and attempting to control the
country's public life.
</P>
<P>
The newly-elected party Shinui, a secular movement with a
platform of objecting to what it calls religious-coercion, will
stay definitely out of the coalition if Shas is included.
</P>
<P>
The Center Party, led by former defense minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, and the United Torah Judaism, an ultra-Orthodox party
of European Jews, are both close to joining the government.
</P>
<P>
If Shas finally joins the government and Meretz stays, then
Barak will have a coalition of more than 75 seats.
</P>
<P>
Even if Meretz chooses to stay out, it will continue to
support the government from the outside, Meretz leader Yossi Sarid
promised to Barak.
</P>
<P>
Suffering a humiliating loss in the parliamentary election last
month, Likud members have been at odds over whether to join the
government. Sharon has become more and more isolated for his
position in favor of joining the government.
</P>
<P>
Also, there has been strong opposition inside the One Israel to
the inclusion of the hard-line Likud, saying the Likud will stand
in the way of the Middle East peace process that Barak has pledged
to revive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Starts Self-Help Program to Fend Off Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Angola's central Huambo province
which witnessed the most fierce fight in the war-ravaged country
has started a self-help program to fend off the grim food crisis
since humanitarian relief from outside the country has become
increasingly difficult.
</P>
<P>
Paulo Cassoma, governor of Huambo, has announced an emergency
agricultural production program to alleviate food supply to the
province.
</P>
<P>
According to the Angola News Agency, the program, estimated to
cost 1.8 million U.S. dollars, is aimed to mobilize local
residents to plant potatoes on about 74,500 hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
Since the civil war renewed in December of last year, over
170,000 refugees have swarmed to the province, putting much
pressure to the relief work.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, constant shellings by the rebel National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has halted international
humanitarian relief efforts in the area.
</P>
<P>
At present, the food reserve in the province has dried up,
giving rise to rampant mal-nutrition.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that in Ukama, in Huambo province, some
18,000 hungry refugees are forced to turn to rats and wild fruits
for a living, as they have run out of food supply after UNITA
forces cut off roads to the town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
