<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African Minister Defends Labor Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Labour market regulations
introduced over recent years did not inhibit job creation, South
African Labor Minister Membathisi Mdladlana said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a debate on President Thabo Mbeki's
state-of-the- nation address, Mdladlana said he also remained
unconvinced that increased deregulation or wage flexibility would
create more employment in the South African economy.
</P>
<P>
"There is sufficient evidence to show that sub-wage depression
and the removal of regulations will not solve the problem of
unemployment that we face," he said, quoted by South African Press
Association.
</P>
<P>
"The reality is that significant sectors of the economy no
longer lend themselves to labor intensive methods.
</P>
<P>
"Increasing the ability to hire or fire workers or driving down
wages in such sections will not necessarily create jobs,"
Mdladlana said.
</P>
<P>
It would rather tend to create a more adversarial climate not
conducive to productivity gains.
</P>
<P>
A recent study showed that in Western economies there was no
clear link between employment protection laws and increased jobs.
</P>
<P>
Instead it argued that tight regulation ensured more stable
jobs, less labor turnover and few unemployed.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 percent of the working population in South Africa
are unemployed, and youths unemployment remained unacceptably
high, according to local media.
</P>
<P>
Mdladlana said he intended to release a 15-point labor plan
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will seek to put in place a labor market dispensation that
will encourage youth employment while minimizing the displacement
effects."
</P>
<P>
Turning to the small business sector as an important area of
employment growth, the minister said he would continue to seek
ways of facilitating the needs of small businesses and ensure they
could continue to generate employment while simultaneously
protecting the rights of the workers they employed.
</P>
<P>
One of the main causes of South Africa's economic woes was the
low level of skills in an environment that was increasingly
experiencing major change in the workplace and a reliance on
methods requiring more skills.
</P>
<P>
Only 20 percent of the economically active population was
skilled or highly skilled and the country's skills profile
compared poorly with other middle income countries.
</P>
<P>
An active skills formation strategy was essential for raising
productivity, increasing the output of goods and services,
reducing unit labour costs, raising profits and employment.
</P>
<P>
"My department is committed to ensure that in the next five
years, firstly the skills of the work force are upgraded to meet
the challenges of globalization and changes in the nature of
production.
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, that skills are provided which can facilitate
infrastructural delivery and the development of micro, small and
medium scale enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Thirdly that the level of investment in education and training
is increased and there is an improved return on this investment
and fourthly, that as a result the employment prospects of youth,
rural women and other vulnerable sectors of the community are
enhanced," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
