<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Peaceful Solution to Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
Monday called for a peaceful solution to the Kashmir dispute
between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal during his meeting with Pakistani Minister
of Kashmir Affairs Abdul Majeed Malik, who was on a three-day
visit to Amman as a special envoy of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said measures must be taken to prevent the situation
from further exacerbation, which he said will pose a threat to the
peace and stability of the region and the world as well.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Malik conveyed a letter from Sharif to
Abdullah on the latest development of the Kashmir crisis and to
explain Pakistan's position on the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on Sunday, Malik stressed the need for a
peaceful solution to the Kashmir crisis, but said his country
will not give up its rights of self-defense.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the use of nuclear weapons will not be
adopted or even considered by Pakistan over the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
However, he refused to directly rule out the possibilities of a
major conventional war between India and Pakistan if Indian
troops crossed the border.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing crisis started after Indian troops launched
campaigns to expel what New Delhi called Pakistan-backed intruders
out of the India-held part of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Troops from both sides have been exchanging fire in Kashmir
over the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
However, Pakistan denied that it is militarily supporting those
guerrillas, saying it only gives moral support to those "freedom
fighters."
</P>
<P>
India has so far rejected Pakistan's proposals to hold talks,
saying no talks are possible before it expels all the intruders
out of its part of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan, both of which exploded their first nuclear
weapons last year, fought three wars in the past half a century,
two over Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
