<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Scotland Racist, Anti-English </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Half of all people in Scotland
believe it is a racist nation and two-thirds say the biggest
problem is anti-English racism, according to a poll published on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey for the Daily Record tabloid found that 66 percent
of some 800 people questioned agreed that many people in Scotland
are anti-English.
</P>
<P>
Half of those questioned said they thought Scotland had an
overall racism problem. This is weeks after Scotland's top law
official said the nation's legal system suffered from
"institutional racism" against ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
Scotland has normally viewed itself as a more tolerant society
than England, where there have been recent high-profile cases of
racism, most notably the 1993 racially-motivated murder of black
teenager Stephen Lawrence by a gang of whites, a Reuters report
said.
</P>
<P>
But comedian Connolly said over the weekend that Scots were
less tolerant than they thought, and blamed what he said was
growing anti-English feeling on the Scottish National Party (SNP),
which regularly polls about 30 percent in elections.
</P>
<P>
"It's entirely their fault, this new racism in Scotland, this
anti-Englishness," Connolly, known for his foul-mouthed stand-up
routines and more recently for film roles like Queen Victoria's
servant in "Mrs Brown" and a loan shark turned artist in "The Debt
Collector", was quoted as telling the Sunday Herald.
</P>
<P>
Advocates for ethnic minorities in Scotland responded to the
survey by saying that while anti-English feeling may exist, it is
the minorities who bear the brunt of real racism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
