<HEADLINE> British, Irish PMs in Last-Ditch Fight to Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern fought on Monday to pull
Northern Ireland's troubled peace accord out of a persistent
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The two prime minister held talks again with the British
province's bitterly divided political parties, who were still
deadlocked over the issue of guerrilla disarmament and stalled
plans for a provincial government that Blair says must be in place
by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A row over plans by the pro-British Orange Order to hold a July
4 parade from the village of Drumcree through a Roman Catholic
enclave in the flashpoint town of Portadown has cast a cloud over
efforts to break the deadlock, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
The parade is expected to take place a week before the climax
of the turbulent "marching season" when Protestants mark historic
battlefield victories over the Catholic Irish.
</P>
<P>
Blair intervened by meeting Orange Order organisers and Roman
Catholic objectors after breaking off from the peace talks at
around midday. But the prospects looked bleak.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, the province's first minister and a key
pro-British Unionist leader, said earlier that he thought "fair
and reasonable" proposals were being struck over Drumcree. But Mac
Cionnaith's comments dimmed hopes of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the British and Irish leaders heralds a fateful
three days for the province, marking the resumption of talks begun
last Friday when they won backing from the feuding parties for key
principles they hope will break the logjam.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Adams, the leader of Sinn Fein, the political arm of the
outlawed Irish Republican Army (IRA), told reporters: "We should
not, any of us, underestimate the seriousness of this last
critical stage of the negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Unionist parties refuse to sit with Sinn Fein in the assembly
until the IRA hands over its weapons, despite Sinn Fein's
statement that it is striving for disarmament but cannot coerce
the IRA.
</P>
<P>
Trimble wanted a straight answer from the Republicans, saying
"what we want to hear from them clearly, unequivocally with no ifs
and no buts is that the Republican movement, not just Sinn Fein,
accept they have an obligation to (disarm) and that they are going
to do so within the timescale set out in the agreement."
</P>
<P>
"If they do not accept this principle, then clearly there is
nothing to talk about," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair has put forward a formula that could pave the way for
Sinn Fein to enter government before the IRA disarms. But he says
the guerrillas must pledge to hand in arms by May 2000 or else the
cabinet would cease to exist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
