<HEADLINE> France Concerned About U.S. Congress Report on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The French government is concerned
about a recent U.S. Congress report on religious cults in Europe,
which criticized European countries for persecuting illegal
religious cults, said the daily Le Monde on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The United States Secretary of State Madelein Albright raised
the issue of ``persecution of religious cults'' with the French
government during her stay in Paris earlier this month, said Le
Monde.
</P>
<P>
The move by Albright has caused great concern of the French
Foreign Ministry, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department published recently a report by a U.S.
Congress commission on ``religious freedom'' abroad, which
fingerpointed France several times for launching investigations
against cult groups.
</P>
<P>
The French parliament has established a commission specializing
in investigating illegal cults in France.
</P>
<P>
The commission, created by the U.S. Congress in 1997, has asked
the U.S. government to exert pressure through diplomatic channel
on foreign countries, including the allies of the United States,
over what it called ``problems of religious freedom.''
</P>
<P>
The recommendations came out after the U.S. Congress adopted a
law on international religious freedom on October 27, 1998, which
threatens to impose sanctions by the U.S. against the countries
which Washington judges have violated religious freedom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
