<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Call for Release of Arrested Jews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has rejected recent call of western countries and
international organizations for release of 13 Iranian Jews
arrested on espionage charges.
</P>
<P>
"At present they are only suspects and no verdict has been
issued about them, therefore, any call for their release before
completion of judicial proceedings will not at all be acceptable
or justifiable," the Islamic Republic News Agency Monday quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the remarks in letters to his counterparts of
several countries, the United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, Secretary General of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) Azeddine Laraki and the U.N. High Commissioner
for Human Rights Mary Robinson.
</P>
<P>
In a response to the arrest, the World Bank recently refused to
grant a 200-million-U.S.-dollar loan to two Iranian development
projects.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said the call for the suspects' release amounts to an
intervention to Iran's sovereignty but he assured a fair trial of
the suspects, who were accused of passing secret and military
information to the United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Both the U.S. and Israel denied any links between their
intelligence services and the arrested Iranian Jews and charged
that the arrest was politically motivated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
