<HEADLINE> Clinton Vows to Strengthen Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
vowed Monday to strengthen Social Security and Medicare as the White
House projected that budget surpluses will be more than one
trillion dollars bigger over the next 15 years than were expected
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Clinton proposed setting aside an additional 543 billion
dollars for Social Security over the next 15 years, which he said
would assure the program's solvency until 2053.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed setting aside 794 billion dollars to
strengthen Medicare, including providing new prescription drug
benefits for the elderly. That is 108 billion dollars more than he
proposed in February, when he released his fiscal 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
"Now we have a chance to do even more to use the fruits of our
prosperity today to strengthen our prospects for tomorrow,"
Clinton told reporters before he left for political fund-raisers
in New York and Conneticut.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's plan included no dramatic increases in the targeted
tax cuts he proposed earlier this year, but he did not rule out
considering deeper tax reductions in discussions with
congressional Republicans later this year.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's proposal was expected to add new fuel to his budget
fight with Republicans lawmakers as the Congressional Budget
Office is planning to unveil its own projections.
</P>
<P>
Clinton administration wants to use surpluses on Social
Security and Medicare while the Republican congressmen try to
return the money to tax-payers by cutting tax.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton also proposed to pay off the total national
debt of 5.7 trillion dollars by 2015.
</P>
<P>
"By 2015, this country can be entirely out of debt," Clinton
said, "if we do not squander the surplus by choosing short-term
gain over long-term national goals."
</P>
<P>
For the current fiscal year, Clinton government expects an
overall budget surplus of 99 billion dollars, the biggest ever
and 20 billion dollars more than it projected in February.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
