<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Income Up While Spending Even Greater </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. personal spending rose
even greater than their income's increase in May, according to the
Commerce Department's report Monday.
</P>
<P>
Personal income -- which includes wages, interest and
government benefits -- rose 0.4 percent last month while their
spending picked up 0.6 percent, the Department said.
</P>
<P>
Since consumer spending has repeatedly outpaced incomes, the
nation's savings rate has set a string of record lows this year.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the savings rate fell to a minus 1.2 percent, even
worse than the previous record of minus 1.0 percent in March and
April.
</P>
<P>
Strong consumer spending propelled the nation's economic
growth, which increased at an annual rate of 4.3 percent in the
first three months of this year. Consumer confidence, meanwhile,
is at a record high, despite the prospects that the Federal
Reserve will begin to raise short-term interest rates at its
meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
The 0.6 percent gain in spending in May followed gains of 0.5
percent in April, 0.6 percent in March, 0.9 percent in February
and 0.5 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
Spending on durable goods jumped 2.2 in May. That followed two
months of declines.
</P>
<P>
Spending on nondurable products, such as food and fuel, also
increased 0.5 percent while spending on services rose 0.3 percent
in May.
</P>
<P>
High demand for labor -- with labor shortages in some regions
and industries -- helped to boost wages. In May, wages rose 0.5
percent, following a 0.6 percent increase the previous month.
However, wages for farm proprietors dropped 13.8 percent last
month.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts believe that one of the major reasons why
U.S.people have let their savings rate fall into negative
territory is because the stock market is at record highs, boosting
people's net worth and making them feel more comfortable about
dipping into savings to fund their spending spree.
</P>
<P>
The robust consumer spending has been the major factor pushing
up economic growth this year. With unemployment at the lowest
level in three decades, the Fed has begun to worry that tight
labor markets will soon increase wage pressures and lead to higher
inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
