<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Given Report on Health System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Review Commission into
the Health Sector presented its report Monday to President Robert
Mugabe after 18 months of research into the country's ailing
health delivery system.
</P>
<P>
Commission chairman Eleuther Tarimo said his team examined four
major areas of the health sector which included problems faced by
health services, human resources, organization and accountability
of services and the financing of the health services.
</P>
<P>
He said staff shortages and poor working conditions, shortages
of essential drugs and the general harsh economic environment had
crippled the country's health delivery system.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the government was going to look at report
seriously so as to see how it could implement some of the
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The president said the inadequacy of resources limited the
government's ability to implement all the recommendations that
were contained in the report.
</P>
<P>
It was important, he said, to have one generation after the
other adopting a health delivery system that could sustain
society.
</P>
<P>
New challenges came in the form of new diseases, new
circumstances, re- occurences of some diseases, said the
president.
</P>
<P>
"We have to try as much as possible to develop a health
delivery system that can sustain healthy families in our society,"
he said, adding that public health education was needed so that
inputs into the sector could have a greater effect.
</P>
<P>
The 10-member commission set up in January 1998 comprised of
officials from various health sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
