<HEADLINE> FA Criticized over United Exemption Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Football Association chiefs came
under fire on Monday after offering holders Manchester United the
chance to pull out of next season's F.A. Cup to play in the new
World Team Cup.
</P>
<P>
United suggested they could skip the inaugural World Team Cup
in Brazil next January if their fixture commitments were not eased.
</P>
<P>
The F.A. responded on Sunday night by offering them exemption
from the F.A. Cup for one season. If United do not play, their
place in Brazil would go to the beaten European Cup finalists from
Germany, who are England's rivals to stage the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
But the offer angered the players' union, supporters' groups
and bookmakers who say the decision cheapens the 127-year-old F.A.
Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Taylor, chief executive of the Professional Footballers'
Association, said United's exemption could prove "very damaging to
the status of the F.A. Cup, the world's premier knock-out cup
competition".
</P>
<P>
Andy Walsh, chairman of the Independent Manchester United
Supporters' Association, said: "This is more to do with world
football politics and pandering to Sepp Blatter."
</P>
<P>
Britain's largest bookmakers, William Hill, were infuriated by
the decision. Spokesman Graham Sharpe said: "This announcement has
thrown betting on the F.A. Cup -- one of the most popular of all
betting competitions -- into disarray.
</P>
<P>
But F.A. executive director David Davies countered: "We had an
unprecedented situation which demanded an unprecedented solution.
</P>
<P>
He added that United's closest rivals in the league last season,
Arsenal and Chelsea, had backed the F.A.'s stance.
</P>
<P>
United, who beat Bayern Munich in the European Cup final last
season following a domestic double of Cup and League triumphs, had
indicated they wanted a bye to the fourth round of the F.A. Cup
next season to ease fixture congestion.
</P>
<P>
They have yet to respond to the F.A.'s offer of complete
exemption but a spokesman said a statement was likely to be issued
by the club on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Eight teams, which will include the champions of the seven FIFA
confederations and the Brazilian champions, are invited to take
part in the new competition which runs from January 5 to 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
