<HEADLINE> Indian PM Denies Secret Deal With Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Caretaker Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee said on Monday that his government was not making
any "secret deal" with Pakistan on ending the current conflict in
Kargil sector of Kashmir while Indian air force continued its
round-the-clock bombing on positions occupied by Pakistan
"intruders."
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee told an all party meeting here to discuss the Kagil
crisis that "nothing but complete and unconditional withdrawal of
intruders will satisfy our requirements."
</P>
<P>
He maintained that there would be no further dialogue so long
as the "incursion" continued, adding that "no proposals or
mediation by third parties will be accepted" by India.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman of the External Affairs Ministry confirmed
Monday that Vajpayee and his Pakistan counterpart Nawaz Sharif had
exchanged messages on the Kargil situation earlier.
</P>
<P>
"These messages were in continuation of their telephonic
discussions of the past few weeks in this context," the spokesman
said at the daily briefing on the on-going conflict between the
two neighbors in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The official spokesman also confirmed that former Pakistan
foreign secretary Niaz Naik had visited New Delhi as special envoy
of Nawaz Sharif over the weekend during which he met Vajpayee and
hid principal secretary Brajesh Mishra, but He refused to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
But reports reaching here said Pakistan Foreign Office
maintained that Naik's tour was "a private visit and it has
nothing to do with Pakistan's foreign policy."
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee reiterated that the on-going military action in Kargil
would not be stopped or scaled down until the "intruders" were
driven away.
</P>
<P>
He told the leaders of all parties that Pakistan action this
time
posed the danger of interdicting India's lines of communication
both to Leh and to Siachen, both are strategic posts hold by
India.
</P>
<P>
He accused Pakistan of seeking to alter the line of control
(LOC) and hoping that, by escalating the ground situation, they
would succeed either in forcing international attention on the
issue, or they would compel India to accept the altered status
quo.
</P>
<P>
As Vajpayee briefed the leaders of all major parities, reports
from Kashmir said Indian troops had foiled a Pakistan attempt to
capture a vital ridge line in southern Siachen Glacier, killing at
least 15 Pakistani soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
