<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starting Dialogue Across The Taiwan Straits (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS) says it hopes to promote a
dialogue across the Taiwan Straits by holding a non-governmental
forum in August or September in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The remark came from ARATS Deputy Secretary General Li Yafei
who met with Jan Jih-horng, the deputy secretary general of Taiwan
's Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Li said that ARATS would like to invite SEF's head or its
deputy secretary-general to the forum and that if SEF accepts the
invitation, they could decide which scholars or other personnel in
Taiwan would participate. The two organizations could also discuss
the time and place of the forum, the number of participants, and
other specific matters, he said.
</P>
<P>
ARATS believes that forums or seminars on cross-straits
relations are a way to fulfill the terms of the 4-point agreement
reached by ARATS President Wang Daohan and SEF Chairman Koo Chen-
fu last October in Shanghai. The first point was to arrange a
cross-straits dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Li said that if SEF did not agree, it could make its own
proposal. Arranging a cross-straits dialogue is an essential part
of preparations for Wang's Taiwan visit this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starting Dialogue Across The Taiwan Straits (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARATS and SEF are both NGOs and forums or seminars they hold
should be authorized dialogues and should be differentiated from
other non-governmental academic symposiums in their significance,
and function.
</P>
<P>
Forums they hold should be hosted by the two organizations and
participants are to be selected by the two organizations, which
have invited scholars and personnel from various fields to discuss
matters. For example, some Taiwanese scholars did accompany Koo
when he visited the mainland last year.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the idea that SEF's functions could be weakened or
difficult to put into practice is impossible, said Li.
</P>
<P>
ARATS has considered the differences of the two organizations
and has suggested that no theme to be set for the forum and that
participants be allowed to speak freely. Taiwanese can discuss
issues that concern them and participants can look for common
points while reserving their differences at the same time.
</P>
<P>
If common points are found, they could help preparations for
the Wang-Koo dialogue, procedural discussions about political
negotiations across the Straits, and the reopening of negotiations
on economic and other issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
