<HEADLINE> Derivatives Key to Future of UK Financial Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 28 (Xinhua) - Derivatives will play a key role in
helping London maintain its position as major international
financial center, a report released by British Invisibles (BI)
Monday said.
</P>
<P>
In the last three years, turnover in the OTC market in London
has more than doubled. The exchanges estimate that international
fees and commissions on exchange contracts alone totalled 1.4bn
pounds in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The UK's share of world turnover rose from 27% to 36% between
1995 and 1998. Nearly a half of the rise in world turnover was
attributable to the growth in activity in London.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of BI's Derivatives Steering Committee, Roy Leighton
said: "Derivatives are at the cutting edge of financial
innovation. Properly used they contribute to financial stability
and prudent enterprise management."
</P>
<P>
A range of innovative products developed for clients in
finance, industry and government around the world. All the main
types of OTC products including interest rates, foreign currency,
equities and commodities are available.
</P>
<P>
The development of electronic platforms, including LIFFE
CONNECTtm. The UK is now able to access foreign derivatives
exchanges and undertake remote clearing.
</P>
<P>
It is believed today's derivatives industry in the UK has its
roots in the 16th century forward trading of commodities in order
to hedge against price risk.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the report, Anthony Belchambers, the Futures and
Options Association's Chief Executive, said: "This report shows
the unprecedented growth that has since taken place in this
industry which has put it at the forefront of the world's
financial markets and made it a significant contributor to the
UK's economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
