<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze on Monday blamed "individual Russian military
commanders" for an alleged violation of its air space, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Georgian leadership has repeatedly stated and now declares
that it is impermissible to impudently violate the air space of
Georgia," Shevardnadze said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to an incident occurred on June 18 when
Russian fighter jets allegedly violated Georgian air space. Moscow
has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
"We have warned and we warn again that violations of the
Georgian air space by Russian aircraft is impermissible," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian Foreign Ministry lodged a note of protest with the
Russian Foreign Ministry shortly after the incident, but the
Russian Air Force Press Service in Moscow said Russian planes had
not violated the air space of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
"None of the MiG-29 fighters or any other aircraft of the
Russian air force had carried out flight missions at the indicated
time near the borders of the named Transcaucasian republic," Tass
quoted officials of the Press Center as saying. 
