<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Foreign Ministers to Meet in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Ministers of Greece and
Turkey will on Wednesday meet in New York to discuss a series of
issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after talks with visiting U.N.
Secretary-General's Special Emissary Carl Bildt, Greek Foreign
Minister George Papandreou said that his proposal for a private
meeting with his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem in New York had
been accepted.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Papandreou and Cem will take place on the
sidelines of a meeting on Kosovo organized by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Describing the acceptance by Cem of a meeting in New York as "a
first positive step," Papandreou said that dialogue with
neighboring Turkey had been a sore point for some years now.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that he did not want nor could he prejudge
the outcome of this dialogue.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to Cem last week, Papandreou proposed a dialogue
on issues including organized crime, drug trafficking and illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
As for Turkey's proposal for dialogue on terrorism, he said
that Greece was not afraid to discuss with any country about the
issue, on the conditions that such a discussion was held within
the framework of international conventions which bind the country
and take into account principles which had become established in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out the possibility of signing an agreement
with its rival on combating terrorism, but only said that it was
too early and nothing had been decided.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at odds over
decades for their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits and the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea, and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Turkey also accuses Greece of assisting the
Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) in its terrorist activities against
its neighbor, but Greece has firmly denied such charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
