<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Speaks About Macao Garrison Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Law on Stationing Troops in
the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) is an important
legal foundation for stationing troops in Macao, according to a
Central Military Commission official in charge of legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that the law follows the guidance of the basic
principle of "one country, two systems" and is in accordance with
the Constitution and the Basic Law of the Macao SAR.
</P>
<P>
The 10th session of the Standing Committee of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC) passed the law today, the second
one the Committee has passed for the Macao SAR following the Basic
Law of the Macao SAR.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that the armed forces are a pillar of
the country and that stationing troops in Macao is a symbol of
China's sovereignty over Macao and an effective way for the
Central Government to control defense in Macao. It is also
conducive to maintaining social stability and economic development
there.
</P>
<P>
He said that in order to guarantee that the troops stationed in
Macao will do their duty in accordance with the law and safeguard
state sovereignty, unity, territorial integrity and the safety of
Macao, the law is necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Speaks About Macao Garrison Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said that the law is significant in four ways: First, it
meets the need to station troops in Macao. The law makes clear the
principles and system of stationing troops in Macao and the rules
governing the activities of the troops, and is the legal
foundation for stationing troops in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Second, it meets the need of guaranteeing that the Central
Government exercises effective administration of defense matters
in the Macao SAR by clarifying the jurisdiction and obligations of
the Central Government and the Government of the Macao SAR on
defense matters and stationing troops. It also sets the basic
Central Government policies on stationing troops in Macao, thus
helping relevant legislation and law enforcement of the Macao SAR.
</P>
<P>
Third, the law meets the need to guarantee that troops
stationed in Macao will fulfill their obligations in accordance
with the law by stating their obligations and jurisdiction in the
defense of Macao, the relations between troops and the government
of the Macao SAR and the duties of military personnel in a
capitalist system that is totally different from that of the
mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Speaks About Macao Garrison Law (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since Macao is an international city, good social security and
order are necessary conditions for social and economic development.
The law makes clear that the stationed troops will guard the
safety of Macao and will not intervene in local affairs, but if it
becomes necessary, the Macao SAR Government can ask the Central
Government to let the troops help maintain security and do
disaster work and exercise relevant law enforcement as appropriate
to their tasks as stated in relevant Macao SAR laws.
</P>
<P>
The law contains 30 articles in six sections and clearly states
the defense duties of the troops, including resisting aggression,
guarding the safety of the Macao SAR, and administering military
facilities.
</P>
<P>
In order to properly handle the relations between the troops
and the Government of the Macao SAR, the law states the specific
duties of the troops and the Government of the Macao SAR in
defense and stationing troops and makes clear the procedures and
rights of the troops in assisting the government of the Macao SAR
in maintaining security and in disaster work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Speaks About Macao Garrison Law (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The law says that military personnel must obey the laws of the
Macao SAR and the national laws.
</P>
<P>
The Macao garrison law has had extensive reference to the
similar Hong Kong law, which has had a good effect in the two
years it has been applied. The real conditions of Macao show that
the main stipulations of the Hong Kong garrison law will be
applicable in Macao, the official said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Macao has its own characteristics in politics,
the law, geography, and society, and for the practical needs of
stationing troops in Macao, the law has a number of stipulations
that show the characteristics of Macao.
</P>
<P>
The reasons for the stipulations are: One, to fully demonstrate
the basic principles of stationing troops in Macao; two, to make
clear the legal guarantees for the troops to perform their
obligations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Speaks About Macao Garrison Law (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Because the original laws of Macao do not say anything about
guaranteeing that troops will fulfill their obligations and
protect military facilities, the law has special stipulations that
the Macao SAR will guarantee by law the rights of the troops when
they fulfill their obligations and that the government of the
Macao SAR is to stop any organizations or individuals from
sabotaging or damaging military facilities.
</P>
<P>
These stipulations say that the Macao SAR is to help the troops
fulfill their obligations and protect military facilities through
legislation, law enforcement, and administrative work.
</P>
<P>
They make it clear that the land the troops use is to be
provided by the government of the Macao SAR free of charge.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the law will play an important role
in the smooth return of Macao to the motherland and in the troops'
fulfilling their obligations and guarding the stability and
development of Macao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tanzania's Economic Reforms Start to Bear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Prolonged droughts and heavy
floods have conspired to hit Tanzania over the past three years,
but failed to prevent the country's economy from forging ahead.
</P>
<P>
During the 1998/99 fiscal year ending June 30, Tanzania's
economic growth rate registered at four percent, compared with 4.2
percent in 1996 and 3.3 percent in 1997. Statistics indicate that
the rates for the three years all stood above Africa's average
level.
</P>
<P>
The positive growth momentum is an indication that after more
than 10 years of reform the country's economy has stabilized and
the reform has started bearing fruits, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Despite its fragile economy, the macro-economic situation in
Tanzania has improved significantly. By the end of April this
year, inflation has dropped to 8.9 percent, compared with 36
percent in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has been able to control its budget
by matching expenditure to revenue collection and by avoiding bank
borrowing, said Finance Minister Daniel Yona while presenting a
budget speech at the parliament earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange reserves have increased and now cover nearly
four months of imports. Also, the value of Tanzanian shilling is
in real terms stable, Yona said.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, foreign grants, investments and confidence in the
economy and government are continuously increasing, he said.
</P>
<P>
Like many other African countries, Tanzania went through a
smooth period of development after independence. Its economy,
however, worsened in the mid-1970s due to droughts in cycle and
pitfalls in domestic policies. In 1980s, commodities were in
acute shortage and production got bogged down.
</P>
<P>
In 1986, the government accepted plans of the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and launched a comprehensive
Economic Recovery Program, which has turned Tanzania from a
centrally planned economy into open markets.
</P>
<P>
Control over foreign exchange has been abolished, local and
foreign banks have been allowed to operate alongside
government-owned banks, and investment regulations were amended
twice to attract private investment from both home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
During the past decade, Tanzania has approved some 1,200
projects worth more than three billion U.S. dollars, most of which
coming from foreign investors. The sum made Tanzania one of the
best foreign investment destinations in sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather Forecast for Major World Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Weather forecast for 11 major
world cities from 20:00 today to 20:00 on June 29, issued by China
's Central Meteorological Station tonight:
</P>
<P>
 Beijing: min. 24 degrees C., max. 35 degrees C., clear to
cloudy, calm to gentle breeze.
</P>
<P>
 Tokyo: min. 21 degrees C., max. 25 degrees C., drizzle, calm
to gentle breeze.
</P>
<P>
 Bangkok: min. 28 degrees C., max. 34 degrees C., cloudy, calm
to gentle breeze.
</P>
<P>
 Sydney: min. 13 degrees C., max. 17 degrees C., overcast,
calm to gentle breeze.
</P>
<P>
 Karachi: min. 29 degrees C., max. 35 degrees C., cloudy, calm
to gentle breeze.
</P>
<P>
