<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Labour Refocuses on Welfare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labour government
launched a new drive on Monday outlining a week of key policy
announcements to help the disadvantaged help themselves.
</P>
<P>
The blizzard of initiatives includes a new one-stop shop to
help the jobless claim their benefits but also look for work,
detailed plans for stakeholder pensions designed to help people of
all incomes save for their old age, plans to stop parts of British
towns becoming ghettos, and a new scheme for training
over-16-year-olds for the new-hitech world.
</P>
<P>
Social Security Secretary Alistair Darling told reporters the
week would show government units working together in an "across
the board assault on poverty and the causes of poverty".
</P>
<P>
The ruling Labour refocused its sights after a stunning defeat
in European parliament elections earlier this month. Its new
strategy rests on a conviction it will win the next election on
domestic ground if it not only delivers but is seen to deliver.
</P>
<P>
Welfare reform is a touchy issue for the Labour Government but
it remains committed to it.
</P>
<P>
Also, policy details will be announced to parliament through
the week but Monday's launch of "One" -- a unified system to deal
with the unemployed -- encapsulates Labour's approach perfectly.
</P>
<P>
"People have the right to expect the government to help them
back into work. But in return, they have the responsibility to
take advantage of that," A Reuters report quoted Darling as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
