<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tanzanian Economic Reforms Start to Bear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
... investment destinations in sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
<P>
To revamp the industrial sector, Tanzania has divested more
than 200 state-owned enterprises, making the sector grow at an
average rate of 6.2 percent annually from 1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
In agriculture, liberalization of the market has boosted
circulation of grain and cash crops.
</P>
<P>
By opening up the tourism sector, tourist arrivals has risen to
480,000 with earnings climbing up to 570 million U.S. dollars this
year, compared with 85,000 visitors and 10.3 million U.S. dollars
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The country's mining sector is expected to attract 500 million
U.S. dollars by the year 2000 after the government provided
legislation and mining incentives in developing gold, diamond and
other mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
Certainly, the bed is not all red roses and Tanzania still has
a lot of drawbacks to address.
</P>
<P>
Trade deficit has enlarged to a deficit of 588 million U.S.
dollars because of unfavorable weather conditions and fluctuation
of the international market in recent years.
</P>
<P>
External debt hovers around eight billion U.S. dollars, making
the government unable to improve poor education and health
services. Population growth rate stands at 2.8 percent, believed
to be too high.
</P>
<P>
Above all, an average per capita income of 210 U.S. dollars
keeps the country in the ranks of world's least developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Despite the problems, Tanzania has basically found a good
reform path as its overall macro-economic situation is sound, said
World Bank Managing Director and Corporate Secretary Zhang
Shengman, who paid a visit to the country earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanians have gained confidence from the economic reforms.
As Zhang put it, "The morale of the private entrepreneurs has
improved a lot."
</P>
<P>
In the coming years, Tanzania will continue to push its
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Major challenges will come from the privatization of
telecommunication, harbor, water supply, power and other
infrastructure utilities, said Minister of State Nassor Malocho
while addressing the parliament this month.
</P>
<P>
The government will amend its tax structure, fight corruption
and intensify international cooperation so as to create an even
better investment environment, Malocho said.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is a higher gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate
of eight and ten percent annually," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
