<HEADLINE> Ugandan Gov't Refutes Bomb Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan security authorities have
refuted a newspaper report which said a bomb was found at a public
rally which was being addressed by President Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Monday by the security authorities said the
bomb detonated in the southwestern district of Mbarara was at
least four kilometers away from the public rally.
</P>
<P>
It called for journalists to get confirmation from local
officials and not to make sensational reports before publicizing
anything.
</P>
<P>
The Monitor daily reported last Saturday that a bomb was found
at the venue where Museveni held a public rally three days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The explosive, which was later described as a hand grenade, was
 reportedly discovered by an unidentified security personnel.
</P>
<P>
The report said the detonation sent town people scampering at
around 5: 00 p.m. near the premises of the resident district
commissioner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
