<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Nations Works to Set Up Judiciary in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Monday
announced its first steps to reestablish the non-existent judicial
system and began to deploy the first team of international police
to the field.
</P>
<P>
The steps are among the world body's continuous efforts to
defuse tensions between ethnic Serb and Albanian communities in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General's acting Special Representative in
Kosovo, Sergio Vieira de Mello, Monday named six legal experts
who will meet Tuesday to select a panel of judges which will
immediately begin addressing the issue of detainees arrested and
held by the peacekeeping force, known as KFOR, throughout the
province.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the United Nations was going to create a "U.N. court"
to adjudicate in Kosovo, the spokesman explained that it would be
using the criminal code of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
except where it might contradict the European Commission's
standards on human rights and any other international standards.
</P>
<P>
"But we need judges," he said, "Right now, as KFOR arrests
people, according to European standards they can only hold them
for 48 hours if they're not brought before a judge. And there are
no judges, so unfortunately they've been arresting people and then
releasing them." He said that it was hoped that the judges would
be appointed this week.
</P>
<P>
De Mello, U.N. under-secretary-general for humanitarian
affairs, had received agreement on the setting up of a sectoral
commission on the appointment of judges during a meeting of the
embryonic political consultative council he held with the Kosovo
Albanian leadership on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who is on an non-official
visit to Britain, said Monday that he would appoint a civil
administrator for Kosovo by the end of this week. However, he
declined to comment on press reports that the appointee would a
European and would be chosen from a list of up to 10 candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
