<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: France, Algeria Expected to Improve Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- After years of tense and sometimes
tempestuous relations, there are growing signs that France and
Algeria are in the process of returning to a normal bilateral
relationship.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French television channel France 3 on
Sunday, Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika invited French
President Jacques Chirac, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, National
Assembly Chairman Laurent Fabius and Senate President Christian
Poncelet to visit Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The invitation, still unanswered by the French leaders, came
after a visit to Algeria last week by French Interior Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement, the first visit to Algiers by a French
government minister in two years.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several years, France and Algeria have disputed
over the military crackdown by the Algerian government against
Islamists.
</P>
<P>
Algeria regards France's criticism of its domestic policy as an
interference into its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
But with the improvement of domestic security situation in
Algeria, and the election of President Bouteflika on April 15,
Algeria and France have been relaxing their relations.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's television interview, Bouteflika said that his hand
"is more than extended" toward France.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was "astonished" that Chirac cannot spend a
half day in Algiers while he has visited the capitals of all other
Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian president also sent a message to President Chirac
on Sunday, expressing his readiness to re-establish "privileged
relations" with Paris on the basis of "mutual respect, friendship
and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
For its part, France is considering resuming the flights of Air
France to Algiers, suspended since December 1994 after a terrorist
attack on an Airbus passenger plane of the air company.
</P>
<P>
France also plans to increase the number of visas to be issued
to Algerians to 150,000 this year, against 85,000 in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0061 </DOCNO>
