<HEADLINE> Mubarak Holds Talks with U.S. Officials on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak on Monday held talks with U.S. officials on the prospect
of the Middle East peace under a new Israeli leader.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, on his first visit to the United States in more than
two years, met National Security Adviser Sandy Berger at Blair
House, government guesthouse for visiting dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
"They had a good discussion, which focused mostly on the
current state of the Middle East peace process," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has for years played an active role in promoting peace
between Israel and its neighbors -- the Palestinians, Syria and
Lebanon. But it put its efforts on hold for most of this year,
in the hope that Israeli voters would turn against Benjamin
Netanyahu, the outgoing prime minister, widely seen as an
obstacle to progress towards the Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
Israelis elected Ehud Barak as prime minister in May and a
new coalition dominated by the left is in the making.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also had meeting on Monday with CIA Director George
Tenet, Commerce Secretary William Daley, leaders of American
Jewish community, Defense Secretary William Cohen and World Bank
President James Wolfensohn. His meeting with President Bill
Clinton will be on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
