<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Get UNDP Help in Locating Minefields in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Teams of mine experts,
medical personnel and mine-sniffing dogs will arrive in Sri Lanka
in July to help locate minefields that pose a grave human security
threat in the northest region of the Jaffna Peninula, long under
the control by rebel fighters in the past, a U.N. agency said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The expert teams will help conduct minefield surveys now being
planned with support from the Mine Action Program in Sri Lanka
under the United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The program, with a budget of 4 million U.S. dollars, is
helping plan the establishment of a mine action center and is
supporting other activities, such as the minefield surveys, to
reduce the danger of landmines in the region.
</P>
<P>
Landmines, left over from years of fighting between Tamil
rebels and government forces, are impeding the resettlement
efforts after severely injuring more than 2,000 Sri Lankans, UNDP
said.
</P>
<P>
The landmine presence, while estimated to affect only one to
two percent of the area's land, has kept people from returning to
communities they fled due to the fighting, UNDP said.
</P>
<P>
The surveys will result in a detailed database that pinpoints
the locations of the minefields. Once identified, the minefield
boundaries will be designated and marked off. Local people are
being trained to participate in the surveys and to beware of
high-risk areas identified, UNDP said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
