<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide E-Commerce to Top $1 Trillion by 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Explosive growth of the
Internet is expected to push purchases over the World Wide Web to
top one trillion U.S. dollars by 2003, according to a report
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Because of the increase in the number of people who make
purchases over the Web, said U.S. market research firm
International Data Corporation (IDC), the growth of the average
transaction size, and the adoption of the Web as a viable vehicle
for business procurement, Internet commerce will grow
substantially.
</P>
<P>
According to IDC, the number of users who make purchases over
the Web will jump from 31 million in 1998 to more than 183 million
in 2003 worldwide. Furthermore, there is ample opportunity to
expand the 183 million as it will represent only 36 percent of all
Web users.
</P>
<P>
Internet commerce is currently U.S.-centric. In 1998, IDC said,
non-U.S. Internet commerce accounted for only 26 percent of
worldwide spending, although 56 percent of Web users resided
outside the United States. By 2003, IDC estimates 65 percent of
Web users will be international, and the United States will
account for less than half worldwide Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
As for reasons for the U.S. focus today, IDC cited higher home
PC penetration and the percentage of business PCs that access the
Internet in the United States than foreign countries. "But this is
changing as Europe and other regions quickly accept the Web," IDC
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
