<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Debates Iraq Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
on Monday began discussing the Iraq issue after U.N. weapons
inspectors left Baghdad over 6 months ago.
</P>
<P>
The core issue is how to overcome the differences among Council
members over lifting sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S. and U.K. air strikes on Iraq, the
Council has been divided on policy towards Baghdad, with Britain
recently proposing that the oil embargo against Iraq be suspended
after a new disarmament agency declares that Iraq has met
obligations on weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Britain's draft resolution for the Security Council,
co-sponsored by the Netherlands and backed by the United Sates,
has been rejected by Iraq which has insisted that the sanctions
should be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Russia, China and France say U.N. sanctions should be lifted
with the disarmament issue becoming a job of the on-going
monitoring verification instead of resuming arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
Sources said each of the Council members reiterated its own
position and the next meeting of the series of informal
discussions is expected to take place next month.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the prospect of a compromise, Russia's U.N.
ambassador Sergei Lavrov said he "doesn't think the issue is ready
for discussion". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
