<HEADLINE> Pak Confirms Sending Special Envoy to New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Highly-placed government sources
Tuesday confirmed news reports that Pakistan had sent a special
envoy to New Delhi a day after the Foreign Office's denial of such
a secret mission, the News Network International (NNI) reported.
</P>
<P>
NNI quoted the sources as saying that Niaz A. Niak was sent to
New Delhi as Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's emissary. Niak held
meetings with India's caretaker Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee and his Principal Secretary R.K. Mishra.
</P>
<P>
Niak's visit to New Delhi took place after Mishra's visit to
Pakistan 11 days later, the sources said, adding that Mishra met
Sharif and Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad in Lahore.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Mishra had brought a message of Vajpayee
for Sharif to call back the so-called infiltrators sent by
Pakistan from the Kargil sector on the Line of Control in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Mishra stayed in Lahore for about seven hours and met Sharif at
his Lahore residence, said the official who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Niak did not carry any written message
from Sharif for his Indian counterpart. The substance of his oral
message was that both sides should sit together and "search for a
diplomatic solution" to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Niak's visit took place in the context of the messages and
phone calls exchanged between the prime ministers of Pakistan and
India over the last few weeks, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In these exchanges, Sharif had emphasized that India must stop
heavy shelling along the Line of Control. He also conveyed
Pakistan's continuing interest in resuming the dialogue process
under the spirit of the Lahore Declaration, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Acting spokesman of Pakistan's Foreign Office Monday also
confirmed Niak's visit, but called it a "private" trip which had
nothing to do with the country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, however, admitted that Niak traveled recently to
Indonesia and some other South East Asian countries to garner
support over the Kargil crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
