<HEADLINE> Pak Denies Indian Allegation on Kidnapping Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Tuesday promptly
rejected the Indian allegation that an Islamabad-based Indian
diplomat had been kidnapped and beaten by Pakistani intelligence
agencies.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Pakistan
strongly dismissed the Indian allegation as a "totally baseless
and malicious charge."
</P>
<P>
Such allegations are part of the propaganda campaign launched
by the Indian government, especially since their military
escalation of the situation along the LoC, in an attempt to malign
Pakistan, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Indian High Commission to Pakistan earlier Tuesday issued a
statement which accused the Pakistani intelligence agencies of
"abducting and keeping in illegal detention" one of its staff
member.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the Indian High Commission said that N. R.
Doraiswamy was kidnapped by 8 to 10 persons when he was on his way
to the embassy at 7:45 a.m. local time (02:45 GMT) and he was
severely beaten in custody for several hours.
</P>
<P>
The latest Indian charge is obviously designed to cover up the
fact that a Pakistani High Commission official in Delhi was
abducted on June 27, said the Pakistani spokesman.
</P>
<P>
India Monday expelled Dil Fayyaz, a staff member of the
Pakistani High Commission to India, with the accusation of his
engagement in what is called "spying" activities.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, who on Monday had said Fayyaz was "mysteriously
disappeared," Tuesday denied the Indian accusation and alleged
that the Indian intelligence agencies "abducted" the diplomat and
kept him in illegal custody for more than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
India's action, which was "in violation of the Vienna
Convention on Diplomatic Relations and the Code of Conduct for
Treatment of Diplomatic Personal in Pakistan and India," can only
serve to vitiate the already tense prevailing atmosphere, said a
Pakistani official statement earlier Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
