<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Urged to Save Youngsters With HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Uganda AIDS Commission launched a
campaign here Tuesday to enhance people's alertness about HIV/AIDS
and pay special attention to young people suffering from the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"The function here aims to arouse people's alertness about the
dangers of the pandemic and young people living with HIV/AIDS are
the special focus, " Anne Nakaweesi, coordinator with the
commission, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Young people living with the disease should have more
productive life and it is every Ugandan's duty to eliminate the
disease in this east African country, she said.
</P>
<P>
Data from the U.S. Bureau of Census show that 1.7 million
Ugandan children have become orphans as a result of AIDS since the
epidemic was found in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
According to the data released by the commission at the
function, more than three million children and young people
worldwide became infected with HIV in 1998. In Uganda, girls are
three to six times more infected than boys aged from 15 to19
years.
</P>
<P>
Affected Ugandan young people include those living in a family
where a relative has HIV or AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
