<HEADLINE> Highlights of Today's Diplomatic News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released by Xinhua today:
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Leaders Meet Pakistani Prime Minister
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, in a meeting with Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif today, voiced the hope that Pakistan
and India would jointly ease the current tense situation in
Kashmir and settle the existing problems through dialogue and
talks.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that "China and Pakistan are close and friendly
neighbors and our bilateral friendship has stood the test of time
and has been proven to be vigorous."
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the National People's Congress Standing
Committee, told Sharif today that China, as a neighboring country
of South Asia, hopes that stability and economic development can
be maintained in the region.
</P>
<P>
Li added that "China firmly maintains that both the nuclear
weapons and missiles race in South Asia and the tensions in
Kashmir are not in the interest of the people there."
</P>
<P>
 FM Spokeswoman Denies Milosevic Seeking Asylum in China
</P>
<P>
China denied today the report that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic has sought political asylum in China. A Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman described the report as groundless.
</P>
<P>
 Lebanese Sovereignty and Territorial Integrity Be Respected
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has always held that the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of Lebanon be respected, Zhang Qiyue,
spokeswoman of the Foreign Ministry, said this afternoon while
commenting on Israel's bombardment of Lebanon last week.
</P>
<P>
She said that "Israel should implement the UN Security Council
Resolution 425 without preconditions and withdraw its troops from
southern Lebanon, so as to help resolve the remaining issues
between the two countries through peaceful negotiation."
</P>
<P>
 Tightening Sensitive Technology Export to HK Unreasonable
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate bill to impose controls on the exports of "
sensitive US technology" to Hong Kong is totally unreasonable and
will bring negative impact on the economic development of Hong
Kong, Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said here today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. congressional allegation that sensitive US technology
was being transferred from Hong Kong to China's mainland is
totally groundless, the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
India, Pakistan Urged to Keep Restraint and Calm
</P>
<P>
China sincerely hopes that India and Pakistan can resolve their
dispute by peaceful means in order to safeguard stability in South
Asia and it urges the two countries to maintain restraint and
calmness, Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's China
visit, Zhang said she believes that the visit will further promote
the existing Sino-Pakistani friendly and cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
Nansha Islands Sovereignty Indisputable
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said today that
Chinese sovereignty over the Nansha Islands and adjacent waters is
indisputable.
</P>
<P>
Zhang made the remarks at a press conference in response to a
question about recent reports that Malaysia has built facilities
on the Yuya Shoal and Boji Reef in China's Nansha Islands.
</P>
<P>
FM Spokeswoman on US-Japan Missile Accord
</P>
<P>
China is concerned about the possible signing of the Memorandum
of Understanding between the United States and Japan on the
development of the Theater Missile Defense (TMD) system, according
to Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue.
</P>
<P>
"China has several times made clear its position on the joint
development of TMD between U.S. and Japan," she said at a regular
press conference this afternoon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
