<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Sports Minister Disunited With PFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- British Sports Minister Tony Banks
and players' bosses found themselves in opposition over how
Manchester United should react to the Football Association's offer
of a "one-off" exemption from next season's FA Cup.
</P>
<P>
Banks told the House of Commons how important it was to allow
the Treble winners to pull out of the competition so they could
take part in FIFA's inaugural World Team Championship in January
next year.
</P>
<P>
If they do not compete, United would be replaced by Bayern
Munich- who come from World Cup 2006 rival hosts Germany - as
Europe's champion representatives in Brazil, Banks warned. But the
Professional Footballers' Association insisted any exemption for
United could prove very damaging to the 127-year-old competition.
</P>
<P>
PFA chief executive Gordon Taylor believes the ideal solution
to the problem would have been a 'bye' into a later round - it
would have to be the fifth round to avoid a clash.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said United's exemption would be "very damaging to the
status of the FA Cup, the world's premier knockout cup competition
".
</P>
<P>
He added: "I would have thought we could think about allowing
any team that won the European Champions League to be seeded to
enter the FA Cup at a later stage.
</P>
<P>
"We can see no reason why there shouldn't be a new rule to give
a club a bye into a later round in the FA Cup in these
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"Manchester United should enter the (World Team) tournament for
the prestige it would bring English football."
</P>
<P>
For Banks, such a compromise is not on the agenda. He told MPs:
"Manchester United's exemption from next season's FA Cup is a one-
off exceptional proposal for exceptional circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"There are two reasons for it. First of all, England has an
unenviable reputation for looking down on new major tournaments.
We refused to enter the World Cup when it was first organized. We
refused to enter the European Cup when it was first begun."
</P>
</TEXT>
