<HEADLINE> GCC FMs to Resume Meeting Next Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states will resume their 71st session in
the Saudi Red Sea port city of Jeddah next Saturday, diplomatic
sources in Riyadh said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are yet to complete the agenda of the proposed
two-day meeting in a bid to close ranks, the sources were quoted
by the Kuwait News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The GCC top diplomats met in the Saudi capital of Riyadh on
June 12 on a number of issues topped by the GCC-Iranian
rapprochement and its possible impact on the territorial dispute
between the United Arab Emirates (UAE) and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The UAE claims sovereignty over the three Gulf islands of Abu
Moussa, Greater and Lesser Tunbs, which are controlled by
Iran. Abu Dhabi fears that the warming up of ties between some GCC
states, especially the Gulf heavyweight Saudi Arabia, and Iran
will relinquish GCC's support to the UAE in the islands dispute.
</P>
<P>
But the GCC ministerial session was suspended with the absence
of a final communique due to differences among members over the
issues discussed and the wording of the communique.
</P>
<P>
The UAE and Saudi Arabia later agreed after a Qatari mediation
on the resumption of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Emir of Qatar Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani, earlier
this month, went to both Riyadh and Abu Dhabi in an effort to
bridge the differences between the two GCC countries.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance established
in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
