<HEADLINE> WB Gives Aid to Zimbabwe's Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC), the private sector arm of the World Bank, said
Tuesday it has committed more than 42 million U.S. dollars to
Zimbabwean private companies during the financial year ending June
30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The assistance comprised equity subscriptions of more than
three million dollars and term loans of more than 39 million
dollars, said Michael Tiller, IFC regional representative.
</P>
<P>
"The IFC will have invested in seven Zimbabwean companies
during that time, in support of projects with a total value of 113
million U.S. dollars, " Tiller said. "Given the risk of further
devaluation of the Zimbabwean dollar, most of IFC's business
partners come from sectors with a substantial export orientation."
</P>
<P>
Asked about the successful rate of companies assisted in the
past three to five years, Tiller said most of the Zimbabwean
companies in IFC's investment portfolio had been successful
commercially.
</P>
<P>
However, a few that depended exclusively on domestic markets
had experienced considerable stress, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said the private sector must be the engine for Zimbabwe's
economic recovery and growth.
</P>
<P>
"It is the private sector that creates value, which expands the
tax base and which provides productive jobs with good salaries and
wages," he was quoted by the Zimbabwe News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Small and medium scale enterprises have a crucial role to play
in this effect," he added.
</P>
<P>
On what could be done to improve the country's investment
climate, Tiller said the single greatest boost to Zimbabwe's
investment climate would come from strict discipline on the
government budget to bring down deficit, reduce the interest
burden and free capital for investment in productive enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The IFC fosters economic growth in the developing world by
financing private sector investments, mobilizing capital in
international financial markets and providing technical assistance
and advice to governments and businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
