<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke062969 -Malaysian Economy on Recovery: Economic Action Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's real gross
domestic product (GDP) is expected to grow by 3.9 percent this
year, according to a statement released by the National Economic
Action Council (NEAC) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Capital controls have been a net
positive, primarily because the authorities have used the window
of opportunity to speedily address bank restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Monetary restraint and credible laws on bankruptcy and
foreclosure have facilitated an effective bank workout, thus
clearing the way for a genuine easing of monetary policy, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Tempered by a still-wide output gap, the Producer Price Index
(PPI) inflation is already deeply negative and this is creating
room for a further decline in interest rates with the Base Lending
Rate (BLR) expected to fall to six percent (a 13-year low) by the
year end, it said.
</P>
<P>
Touching on exports, it said Malaysia's export performance has
been the most impressive in Asia (after the Philippines) over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
"We expect a considerable acceleration in export growth over
the next five months aided by a low-base effect, as Malaysian
exporters continue to benefit from the stable and competitive
ringgit," it added.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that exports will receive a further fillip from
the strength of new U.S. orders for electronic components.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both the trade and current accounts have continued
to rise year-on-year and are likely to continue doing so through
the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Only a massive fiscal stimulus coupled with monetary
accommodation can cause import growth to exceed export growth in
the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"For the whole year, we expect exports to grow 7.8 percent and
imports to rise 6.7 percent," it added.
</P>
<P>
It was also noted that the central bank liquidity support for
the banking system had declined dramatically over the past 15
months from 12.5 percent of GDP in February 1998 to 0.7 percent of
GDP in May 1999, which was even lower than the 1.6 percent figure
at end 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the effective carve-out of non-performing loans
(NPLs) and bank recapitalization are expected to be completed by
the third quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The rise in asset prices in the interim would be also expected
to bolster the confidence of banks along with the value of loan
collateral.
</P>
<P>
For next year, it said the real GDP is expected to grow five
percent, with the CPI inflation accelerating to 3.1 percent from
this year's expected average of 2.4 percent as the current account
surplus declines to 9 percent of GDP. 
</P>
