<HEADLINE> Russia Calls for Strengthening of U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said here Tuesday that Moscow will be pressing for the
consolidation of the United Nations, the international
organization that bears the responsibility for the maintenance of
peace and security.
</P>
<P>
At a time when world processes are assuming a global scale and
a multipolar structure is forming in the world, no other
organization can meet demands of the times, Ivanov told a
gathering marking the 90th birthday of Andrei Gromyko, who served
as Soviet foreign minister from 1957 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
"The events in Yugoslavia and regarding Iraq showed that some
countries still wish to act bypassing resolutions of the U.N.
Security Council," Ivanov said, noting that "Russia condemns any
violation of human rights and violations of international
humanitarian law."
</P>
<P>
He said Moscow's relations with the United States and NATO were
strained by the events in Yugoslavia and regarding Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Russia suspended its relations with NATO after the military
bloc launched an air campaign against Yugoslavia on March 24.
Limited contacts resumed Monday when a group of Russian officials
went to Brussels to discuss cooperation in peacekeeping operations
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Now that the military operations against Yugoslavia have
stopped, we shall consider what should be done next," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Moscow's objection to NATO's eastward expansion
and described it as "a major political error undermining our
relations."
</P>
<P>
Ivanov stressed that Russia would be guided by its own
interests when dealing with NATO member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
