<HEADLINE> Preparing For Possible Summer Flooding In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The rainy season has started and
the flood season on the Yangtze River is approaching and the
Province of Jiangxi, which had a lot of damage in last summer's
floods, is taking no chances in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
According to the meteorology and flood control department there,
the northern and central parts of the Jiangxi, especially those
along the Yangtze, have had frequent rainfall or heavy rainstorms
since the 23rd of this month.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Jiujiang, where the Yangtze went over the dyke
last year, the river's water level has been rising these days,
authorities say. According to a Jiujiang government official, the
city has 115 emergency flood-fighting squads with more than 20,000
people to patrol the river dyke in the Jiujiang area. The squads
are equipped with nearly a million straw bags, 2.6 million plastic
bags, and more than 2 million cubic meters of stones.
</P>
<P>
Armed police stationed in Jiujiang and the local public
security personnel recently held a joint flood-fighting and
emergency rescue maneuver that dealt with rescuing people from
floodwaters, building temporary dykes, and filling dam breaches.
The provincial government has also sent 4 inspection teams to
check on flood preparations in Jiujiang and other cities and
regions.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial Flood Control Office's Internet Center has also
opened a special website to provide up-to-date weather, water, and
other information across the province.
</P>
<P>
The entire Yangtze River basin was hit by the worst floods in
decades last summer that killed more than 3,000 people and caused
200 billion yuan (about 25 billion U.S. dollars) worth of damage.
</P>
<P>
Summer rains cause extensive flooding and often deaths in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
