<HEADLINE> France Urges Turkey to Reverse Death Sentence on Ocalan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- France has called on Turkey to
reverse its death sentence on Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan,
who was convicted of separatism and terrorism by a three-judge
court early on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This verdict is not definitive yet. Turkey has not executed
anyone on death sentence since 1984. We hope that this situation
will continue," said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne
Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
She said that France will link this with Turkey's long-time
efforts to enter the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"Opposition to death penalty is a matter of principle for
France and its European partners," she said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the spokeswoman reaffirmed France's
determination to condemn and combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The president of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) has a number
of channels of appeal open to him. The death sentence goes
automatically to the appellate court. The court could either rule
for a re-trial, or uphold the sentence.
</P>
<P>
If upheld, the case is passed on to the Turkish Parliament and
President Suleyman Demirel for further approval. If Ocalan finally
has to mount the gallows, the appealing process may take at least
six months, possibly as long as 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
