<HEADLINE> Central Chinese City Pumping Rain Water From Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-three pump stations and
thousands of people have been working round the clock to get the
water off the streets in part of this central Chinese city on the
Yangtze River, which has been hit by heavy rains for the past week.
</P>
<P>
Local meteorologists report that 432 mm of rain has fallen on
the city since last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Buses had to change their routes when three major avenues were
flooded and people in at least two heavily-populated neighborhoods
were isolated by a half-meter of water left standing.
</P>
<P>
The pumps have been moving water out of the city at a rate of
310 cubic meters per second and road surfaces finally began to
appear above the flood waters as the rain eased off a bit this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The weather forecast calls for more rainstorms over the next
two days and more than 1,000 municipal workers and 1,000 police
have been put on full alert.  
</P>
