<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: Kosovo Not Precedent for Future Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said Monday that NATO's bombing against
Yugoslavia should not be interpreted as a signal that the alliance
will intervene in future conflicts elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
"Some hope, and others fear, that Kosovo will be a precedent
for similar interventions around the globe," Albright told the
Council on Foreign Relations in New York.
</P>
<P>
"I would caution against any such sweeping conclusions,"
Albright was quoted by an Associated Press report.
</P>
<P>
The statement reflects a "subtle change" of the Clinton
administration's policy on NATO's future role, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Before the Kosovo crisis, the administration had pressed NATO
members to consider expanding the defensive alliance's reach
beyond Europe as a way of maintaining an important post-Cold War
role in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Every circumstance is unique," Albright said, adding that NATO
is not a global institution, but a European and Atlantic one. Any
decision to use force against other countries should be made by
the president after weighing a host of factors, she said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Kosovo's future, Albright said she understood the
ethnic Albanian desire for Kosovo's independence.
</P>
<P>
"In the future, Kosovars will have something they have never
had, which is genuine self-government," she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright expressed hope for the future of Kosovo,
citing strong commitments by the U.S. and Europe to rebuild the
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
