<HEADLINE> Rockets to Trade Olajuwon to Raptors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- NBA 50 greatest star Hakeem
Olajuwon of the Houston Rockets is likely to be traded to the
Toronto Raptors for two players and two first-round draft picks,
the Houston Chronicle reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources close to the talks as saying
discussions have been going on for about two weeks. But the
sources said talks had not been completed as of late Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rockets officials refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing is there will be fewer free agents in the
future under the new collective bargaining agreement," a source
close to the talks said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Olajuwon, a 12-time NBA All-Star and the Rockets' most
celebrated player in a 15-year NBA career, led them to back-to-
back NBA championships in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Trades cannot be made until August 1, so the Raptors would have
to select players on the Rockets' behalf during Wednesday's 1999
NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
Houston would acquire the Raptors fifth and the 12th pick in
the first round selection. The Raptors also would send former
Rockets center-forward Kevin Willis and swingman Doug Christie to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
The Rockets, who have the No. 22 pick in the first round, have
been looking to move up in the draft. The No. 5 pick would be the
team's highest since they chose Olajuwon first overall in 1984.
</P>
<P>
The deal also could affect Houston forward Charles Barkley, who
is considering retirement and said he wanted to return only if he
thought the Rockets were title contenders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
