<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese Development and Reconstruction Council
has signed an agreement with the European Union on a project for
investment planning program.
</P>
<P>
A council statement said the project aims to boost the
capability of planning and project management of public
establishments and ministries, and modernization of the
infrastructure in Lebanon, the Arabic Al Hayat daily reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project amounts to 30 million Euro (31.2
million U.S. dollars), of which the EU will offer 25 million Euro
(26 million dollars) as a grant.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Moroccan Minister of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation
Mohamed Bin Issa has emphasized that his country will not allow
the European fishing fleet to fish in Moroccan territorial waters
unless an agreement is concluded with a new version on bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Morocco opposes the renewal of the
current maritime fishing agreement with the EU, which expires
last November 30, the Arabic Alam Al Yom reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Morocco, he added, expected to hear from the EU on a new
agreement that stipulates new versions of cooperation so that the
Spanish fleet might continue its activities in Moroccan waters.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Omani Minister of Commerce and Industry Maqbool Bin
Ali Sultan has announced the Omani government's approval of
establishing a free zone in the Salala port-city.
</P>
<P>
A well-informed source said that the Salala Port Services
Company, an Omani limited liability company, has been charged
with the task of managing the project. It will undertake the
development of the first phase of the free zone, the Alam Al Yom
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Salala free zone would be financed in large
part by the private sector, and would be developed over a number
of phases to ensure appropriate planning for sound industrial
development of the zone.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates Airways in London has
signed a contract of 83.4 million dollars in order to receive the
third and long-range airbus A-330/200 by July 7, at the French city
of Toulouse where the aircraft is being built.
</P>
<P>
This is one of 18 aircraft equipped with Rolls Royce engines.
</P>
<P>
UAE Airways sources said that the airplanes requested by the
UAE includes three Boeings and six long-range A-340/500 aircraft
while retaining the right to buy four Boeing 777s, five airbus
330/200s and 10 airbus A-340/500s.
</P>
<P>
The UAE airways operates flights to 47 destinations in 37
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
