<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Pay Last Respects to 1st Black Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanians of all walks of
life Tuesday paid their last respects to Chief Adam Sapi Mkwawa,
the first black Speaker of Parliament since Tanzania's
independence from the British colonial rule in 1961.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa, Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye, and
Parliament Speaker Pius Msekwa joined other seniors officials and
diplomats as well as common people in paying their last respects
to Mkwawa, whose face could be seen through a half-open coffin
cover.
</P>
<P>
In his message of condolence, Mkapa said Mkwawa served the
national assembly as a speaker with dedication and highest
commitment and the nation will miss his most sought wisdom,
experience and ability.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sumaye praised Mkwawa as a fighter in the
forefront of the independence struggle and a leader with unique
experience and capability to man the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa will lead a high-powered government delegation
to the burial at Mkwawa's home village Karenga in Iringa Region
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mkwawa died last Friday at the age of 79 at the Muhimbili
Medical Center in Dar es Salaam after a 10-day battle with high
blood pressure. Mkwawa was survived by a widow and 10 children.
</P>
<P>
He began his career as the first black parliament speaker on
November 27,

1962 when the first speaker H. Karimjee of Asian origin retired.
</P>
<P>
Born on June 14, 1920, Mkwawa succeeded his father Chief Sapi
Mkwawa as a chief of the Wahehe Tribe in Iringa in 1940 and held
the position till 1962 when the chiefdom was abolished and he
became the Parliament Speaker.
</P>
<P>
Mkwawa is the grandson of the well-known Chief Mkwawa who
fought an armed struggle against the then German colonists late
last century.
</P>
<P>
Mkwawa took his primary education at Karenga Primary School in
1928 and joined the Makerere University in Uganda in 1940 to study
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
However, he didn't complete the studies in the same year as he
was summoned back home upon the death of his father. He was later
enthroned as Chief of the powerful Wahehe Tribe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
