<HEADLINE> Panda Protection Foundation Debuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A Giant Panda protection
foundation was established today by the China Wildlife Protection
Association and the Japanese Future Generations Alliance
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the "Friends of the Giant Panda" Foundation is
to protect the panda and other wildlife and to maintain harmony
between human and nature.
</P>
<P>
Ma Fu, the vice-director of China's State Forestry
Administration, said during an opening ceremony here today that
over 95 percent of the wild pandas have been given some form of
protection in 25 nature reserves on 10,726 square kilometers of
ground since a panda protection project was begun in China in 1992.
</P>
<P>
However, protecting the Giant Panda and other forms of wildlife
requires a joint effort of all of society. The foundation sets a
good example for cooperation between China and large enterprises
around the world.
</P>
<P>
Its major tasks include supporting scientific research on
protecting the panda and other forms of wildlife and their
habitats and providing awards for those who make an outstanding
contribution to this work.
</P>
<P>
So far, 2.1 million yuan (about 253,000 U.S. dollars) has been
raised for the foundation.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is unique to China and only about 1,000 now
live in the wild and an estimated 100 in captivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency Launches New Program in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) announced Tuesday that it has signed a
42-billion-shilling (30 million U.S. dollars) country program with
the Ugandan government to run parallel with its current relief and
recovery operations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The new five-year development package aims to provide Uganda's
rural poor with productive assets and incomes in order to
strengthen their ability to cope with recurring man-made and
natural calamities, according to a press release issued by the WFP
in Ugandan capital Kampala.
</P>
<P>
The program focuses on agricultural production and marketing,
primary education, and vocational training of orphans and street
children, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Although over 80 percent of Ugandans are employed in
agriculture, the majority of them lack access to markets, with
many producing fewer crops or selling subsistence food to meet
their minimal cash requirements.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, civil wars in neighboring countries,
repeated natural disasters and rebel incursions have forced half a
million people to remain dependent on food aid.
</P>
<P>
"Like all humanitarian agencies, the WFP wants to work itself
out of a job," said Michael Jones, WFP's deputy country director
in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
"The best way to achieve this is to help people harness the
skills they have developed for their day-to-day survival," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The planned program will target the poorest of the poor while
concentrating resources on the most impoverished areas of northern
and western Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Over the next five years, the WFP will place priority on food
security, education and training, the press release said, adding
that particular attention will be paid to women, teenage girls who
trail far behind males in virtually all objective indicators of
human welfare.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda since 1971, the WFP has completed 62 development
projects and relief operations at a total cost of 262 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The organization's current relief and recovery operations in
the country are valued at 54 million dollars per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
