<HEADLINE> Thai PM Confirms Receiving Resignation Letters From SAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
confirmed Tuesday afternoon that he has received resignation
letters from two ministers from the Social Action Party (SAP).
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the Government House after the weekly cabinet
meeting, Chuan said he had informed the cabinet meeting about the
resignations of Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Science,
Technology and Environment Suvit Khunkitti and Deputy Science
Minister Ravee Hiranchote.
</P>
<P>
So far, the prime minister has received no resignation letter
from the last SAP minister, Suriya Chuengrungruangkit, who holds
the deputy industry minister's post.
</P>
<P>
Chuan avoided to answer the question about whether the
resignations of Suvit, the former SAP leader, and Ravee mean the
SAP's quitting from the coalition government, saying only, "It was
hard to say."
</P>
<P>
Chuan said the rift within the SAP is an internal affair of the
party only though it has certain influence on the government.
Parties within the coalition are cooperating closely, he said.
</P>
<P>
Different factions in the SAP are struggling for cabinet seats
and  Suvit had been asked to hand in his science portfolio.
</P>
<P>
They also wanted Ravee, who is in Suvit's camp, to vacant his
post as deputy science minister.
</P>
<P>
Suvit refused to give up the science minister post but offered
deputy prime ministership instead. He also fought back by
resigning as party leader, forcing an executive election on July
2, which he is confident of winning. 
</P>
