<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-Year Old Relics Found in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
unearthed numerous precious historical relics dating back to the
Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220 A.D.) and the Jin Dynasty (1115-1234) in
Suibin County, Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The relics, which were excavated from a tomb of the Jin Dynasty,
include one gold coin of the Han Dynasty and nine copper coins and
a jade ornament of the Jin Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Pingchun, a local archaeologist, said that the gold coin
is about 1.5 mm thick and 3.4 cm in diameter. It was made in the
seventh year A.D.
</P>
<P>
The bronze coins are about 1.2 mm thick and 2.5 cm in diameter.
Eight of them were used as currency and one as an ornament of luck.
</P>
<P>
The historical relics will provide valuable clues for the study
and research into the ancient culture and social customs in the
area, the birthplace of the Jin Dynasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
