<HEADLINE> Rural Chinese Women Keen to Learn Computer Skills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Social development in China has
meant that increasing numbers of rural people are expected to
understand advanced technology to help the agricultural industry
change with the times.
</P>
<P>
As a result many are learning computer skills and in the city
of Anshan in northeast China's Liaoning province, the local
committee has invested 800,000 in buying 20 computers,
constructing a special computer room and hiring teachers to
provide free training for the inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 women applied for the training with 40 of them
attending the first term learning to type, design forms and even
to carry out small editing projects, and all in less than 20 days.
</P>
<P>
One such is Chen Guiron, a 44-year old woman who said: "I'm now
able to skillfully operate a computer which is of great benefit to
the community."
</P>
<P>
A further twenty of her friends and neighbors are also learning
computer skills. "We want to make use of the opportunity to gain
more knowledge so as to keep up with the country's overall social
development," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Her township now has 25 enterprises of its own, handing in
taxes last year of 7.6 million yuan (about 912,000 U.S.dollars),
with its total net income reaching 3 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
It also provides free nine-year compulsory education to all the
local children, and at the same time gives a monthly allocation of
20 yuan to those aged over 60. It has also invested a total of
five million yuan in the construction of green-houses, peach
gardens and animal breeding centers.
</P>
<P>
Rural people are still willing to learn more, though their per
capita annual income didn't exceed 5,000 in 1998. And Sun Wei, a
mother of a four-year old child, was among the first to pay for
herself to learn computer operations.
</P>
<P>
And Wang Hong, a 32-year old woman said: "We want to buy a
computer of our own later for use by both us and our children."
</P>
</TEXT>
