<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loan for China's Environmental Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank approved
Tuesday a 300 million U.S. dollar loan to China for improving
water quality and flood control in the heavily polluted Suzhou
Creek which flows through the heart of Shanghai in China.
</P>
<P>
ADB said in a news release that the Suzhou Creek Rehabilitation
Project will improve the environment, living conditions and public
health standards of about 3 million people living in the project
area.
</P>
<P>
The Suzhou Creek is severely polluted with large discharge of
untreated agricultural, industrial and municipal wastewater and
solid waste, ADB said.
</P>
<P>
According to the ADB, the aim of the project is to restore
water quality of the creek by 2004 and relocate nightsoil and
solid waste collection wharves along the creek's banks.
</P>
<P>
The project will also facilitate interceptor sewers, pumping
stations, a wastewater treatment plant and flow control structures
on tributaries besides building greenbelts along both banks of the
creek, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loan will come from its ordinary capital resources at
the bank's pool-based variable lending rate for U.S. dollar loans,
with a commitment charge of 0.75 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
The bank's loan, accounting for about one-third of the total
project cost of 876 million dollars, will have a maturity of 25
years, including a grace period of five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
