<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Genocide Suspect's Case Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The extradition case
concerning Bernard Ntuyahaga, a former army officer wanted by both
Rwanda and Belgium for his role in the 1994 Rwanda genocide, has
been adjourned to July 14.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga was brought before the Kisutu Resident Magistrate's
Court in Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam on Tuesday morning, but a
Belgian lawyer demanded by him did not appear.
</P>
<P>
Major Ntuyahaga, former head of logistics at Kigali military
camp in Rwanda, allegedly murdered former Rwandan Prime Minister
Agathe Uwiningiyimana and 10 Belgium U.N. peace-keepers escorting
her.
</P>
<P>
At present, he is defended by Tanzanian lawyer, Dr. Jwain
Mwaikusa, a teacher at the Law Department of the University of Dar
es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
However, the accused alleged that he has language problems and
needs another counsel, Luc de Temmerman of Belgium, to assist Dr.
Mwaikusa.
</P>
<P>
During the past two weeks, Mwaikusa told the court that he has
communicated with Temmerman by E-mail, asking for Belgian lawyer's
curriculum vitae (CV).
</P>
<P>
The lawyer's resume was mailed to the university and did not
reach Dr. Mwaikusa's hand until Monday, and essential documents
like professional certificates and a letter of reference were
missing, Dr. Mwaikusa said.
</P>
<P>
He told the Principal Resident Magistrate Projestus Rugazia
that he has just sent a message to Temmerman to get those
documents and fax to him as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The documents are supposed to be handed over to Tanzania's High
Court, which will consider whether or not to allow Temmerman to
act as Ntuyahaga's counsel.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga's case has been adjourned several times since it was
opened on May 12.
</P>
<P>
The 47-year-old man fell into the hand of the Tanzanian
government in March this year after the International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR), based in Arusha in north Tanzania,
dropped charges of genocide and crimes against humanity against
him and released him.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga was re-arrested by the Tanzanian police and wanted by
both Rwanda and Belgium for extradition and trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
