<HEADLINE> Pakistan Accuses India of Abducting Embassy Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Tuesday accused
India of abducting its official in New Delhi, saying it is "a
clear violation of the Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations."
</P>
<P>
A press release by the Foreign Office said that Dil Fayyaz, an
official of the Pakistani High Commission in New Delhi, who was
missing since Sunday evening, had been abducted by the Indian
intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
Fayyaz was "kept in their illegal custody for more than 24
hours under false charges while also being physically manhandled,"
said the press release.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Foreign Ministry and its High Commissioner in New
Delhi have rejected the allegations leveled by the Indian side
against Fayyaz.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Press Trust of India (PTI), India
Monday expelled Fayyaz for "spying." Fayyaz was detained by Uttar
Pradesh police in the neighboring district of Ghaziabad for
violating the official secrets act.
</P>
<P>
PTI quoted a police source as saying that Fayyaz was
apprehended by Uttar Pradesh police and was brought in New Delhi
Monday and handed over to the Pakistani High Commission the same
day.
</P>
<P>
The press release by Pakistan's Foreign Office said that "under
no circumstances can the official's abduction and detention be
justified or condoned."
</P>
<P>
"Such actions in violation of existing agreements and norms can
only serve to vitiate the already tense prevailing atmosphere," it
said. 
</P>
