<HEADLINE> Israel Orders Tighter Security After PKK Leader's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government ordered
its embassies and consulates around the world to beef up security
Tuesday after Turkey sentenced Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan to death for treason.
</P>
<P>
The measures were taken as precautions for possible outbreaks
of violence by Kurdish groups. Ocalan's Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK) has warned of bloodshed if its leader was sentenced to
death, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Four Kurds were killed by Israeli security guards in Berlin
when the Israeli consulate was stormed by Kurdish demonstrators
on February 17, two days after Ocalan was captured by Turkish
agents in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has vehemently denied reports that
Israel's spy agency Mossad has played a role in the capture of the
PKK leader, who has led a 15-year war for Kurdish autonomy in
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman was quoted by Israel Radio as
reiterating Tuesday that Israel has never been involved in the
case.
</P>
<P>
A PKK spokesman in Brussels also told Israel Radio Tuesday
that his group "has nothing against Israel," but expected an
apology from the Israeli government for the killing of the four
Kurdish protesters. 
</P>
