<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Ministers From Social Action Party Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister and
Science Minister Suvit Khunkitti and his science deputy Ravee
Hiranchote, both from the Social Action Party (SAP), resigned
Tuesday pending a government reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Suvit said his resignation is aimed at paving the way for the
government reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
However, local political analysts said his resignation is the
latest result of the struggle within the Social Action Party over
the cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
Factions led by party advisor Rakkiat Sukthana and
Secretary-General Somsak Thepsuthin had demanded that Suvit, who
was the party's leader, hand in his science minister portfolio and
keep only the deputy prime minister's post.
</P>
<P>
They also wanted Ravee, who is in Suvit's camp, to vacant his
seat.
</P>
<P>
However, Suvit refused to yield the science post to Somsak,
offering only his deputy prime ministership instead.
</P>
<P>
When the Rakkiat and Somsak factions, which control nine of the
party's 20 seats in the lower house, threatened to pull out of the
government, Suvit resigned last week from the SAP leadership to
force a new administrative committee election on July 2, which he
is confident of winning.
</P>
<P>
Montri Pongpanich, who once held an iron grip on the SAP and is
now in semi-retirement, was thought to be the only person who
could stop the party from breaking up and thus was invited to mend
the rift. But his mediation ended in failure when Suvit rejected
his resolution.
</P>
<P>
The seven-party coalition government enjoys a 257 majority in
the 393-strong House of Representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
