<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Debate Anti-Corruption Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's President Olusegun
Obasanjo is seeking to give extensive powers to an anti-corruption
agency to be set up if the bill submitted by him could be passed
by the National Assembly, reported Nigeria Newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 46-page bill, which is the first bill the president
submitted to the Nigeria's top legislature, is expected to be
circulated Tuesday to members of the senate and House of
Representatives, preparatory to the first reading of it, said the
Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Extensive powers, including that to seize property found to
have been illegally acquired, are being sought by Obasanjo in the
bill for the proposed agency.
</P>
<P>
The bill also requires members of the public to report to the
agency persons believed to have suspicious wealth not
commensurate with his known source of income.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill proposes to have the anti-corruption agency work
side by side with the code of conduct bureau. It was learnt that
the agency may empowered to examine declarations of public
officers forwarded to the ethics bureau.
</P>
<P>
Senate President Chief Evan Eweren, who received the bill
Wednesday, last week from Alhaji Kashim Iman acting as National
Assembly presidential liaison officer, assured that the upper
house would support Obasanjo by working guideline on the document.
</P>
<P>
Clerk of the Senate, Gabriel Omoniyi, is expected to formally
introduce the bill when the senate convenes Tuesday morning, as a
first reading.
</P>
<P>
Representatives had theirs last week, and are expected to
continue their deliberations Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
