<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Vote Counting Needs More Time, Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Indonesian
Election Committee (PPI) Jacob Tobing Tuesday said the General
Election Commission (KPU) might not finish its national vote
counting before July 8.
</P>
<P>
"The time will not be sufficient if there is no extension for
vote counting," Tobing said before a plenary session of the KPU.
</P>
<P>
There is no indication that the commission will discuss the
possibility of extending the time limit as it is still trying to
find a way to finish the counting on schedule, Tobing said.
</P>
<P>
The KPU is expected to finish the national ballot counting for
the elections of the House of Representatives (DPR) as well as
municipal and provincial-level houses (DPRD II and DPRD I) before
July 8.
</P>
<P>
Tobing said the PPI's counting has reached some 75 percent of
the total 117.8 million votes throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, KPU Chairman Rudini said the commission is still
trying to find the best solution for regions which have yet to
send in the vote counting results.
</P>
<P>
"We have to find a way so those data can be sent (to Jakarta)
soon," Rudini said.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 327 municipalities in Indonesia, only 127 of them
have reported the results of the ballot counting.
</P>
<P>
The slow entry of data is not because of a failure in the
system, but it is merely a problem of data entry, Rudini added.
</P>
<P>
Official data collected by the KPU, based on votes counted till
Tuesday morning, showed the Indonesian Democratic Party of
Struggle (PDI-P) in the lead with 22.96 million votes, followed by
Golkar Party with 12.1 million), National Awakening Party (PKB)
11.1 million, United Development Party (PPP) 6.35 million and
National Mandate Party (PAN) 4.34 million.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial results collected by the official
Antara News Agency from the provincial chapters of PPI, until
Tuesday morning, PDI-P remained in the lead with 33.97 million
votes or 34.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Golkar Party followed with 22 million votes (22.29 percent),
PKB 12.93 million votes (12.98 percent), PPP 10.5 million votes
(10.57 percent) and PAN 6.88 million votes (6.92 percent).
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the election on June
7 to compete for 462 of the 500 seats in the DPR. The remaining 38
seats are reserved for the military, whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
KPU officials stressed that the results of the election will be
determined by the official data issued by the KPU, and other data
are unofficial. 
</P>
