<HEADLINE> France Reduces Troop Deployment in South Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- France is reducing its troop
deployment in the South Pacific region with the dissolving of a
company of navy troops and an army battalion in New Caledonia.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported that a ceremony of closing
the camp of a navy company, which has served in New Caledonia
since 1962, was held on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
New Caledonia, France's largest overseas territory in the South
Pacific, is expected to gain independence in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
A battalion of French army on the archipelago will also be
dissolved on July 31, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
France has recently withdrawn a unit of Foreign Legionnaire
mercenary troops from the Polynesian islands, which used to be
France's basis for launching nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of French troops in New Caledonia now stands at
3,400 and it will be reduced to 3,000 by the year 2002, said AFP.
</P>
</TEXT>
