<HEADLINE> Symposium Targets Sino-Japanese Cooperation on Polar Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- More than 40 overseas and
domestic experts in polar research gathered here today to exchange
views on the latest progress into research of high-altitude
atmospheric physics in the South Pole and discuss further Sino-
Japanese cooperation in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The four day symposium has been sponsored by Chinese and
Japanese Polar Research Institutions and delegates include
scientists from China, Japan, Norway and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Ever since a scientific agreement was signed between China and
Japan in August 1994, the two countries have sent regular teams of
scientists, a total of 15, to the South Pole for on site
observations of high-altitude atmospherics, obtaining large
amounts of materials and data.
</P>
<P>
The Polar Research Institute of China and the National
Institute of Polar Research of Japan will sign new agreements to
expand cooperation in polar research during the current symposium,
organizers have revealed.  
</P>
