<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Loans Used To Battle Acid Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign loans are to be used in
the battle to treat urban pollution in China with Liuzhou City in
southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region the first city
to take advantage of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
It has secured a package of loans worth 10.7 billion Japanese
yen (about 88 million US dollars) from the Japan's Overseas
Economic Cooperation Fund to tackle its acid rain problem.
</P>
<P>
Liuzhou is one of China's four worst areas in terms of acid
rain pollution. The excessive amount of sulfur dioxide discharge
into the air is generally considered to be the main cause and the
city suffers from three times the national second-degree standard
of such pollution.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be used in six sub-projects, which include
replacing residential use of coal with coal gas and treating
residential and industrial waste.
</P>
<P>
The treatment is expected to annually reduce sulfur discharges
by 36,200 tons, soot by 7,700 tons and the city's industrial
sewage by 2 million tons.
</P>
<P>
International procurement and land requisition for the projects
have already started.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
