<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Says 98 Rebels Killed in New Offensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government said
Tuesday that its troops had recovered the bodies of 98 Tamil
rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) killed in a
new offensive in the northern Wanni area.
</P>
<P>
Troops Monday also recovered 43 anti-personnel mines from the
newly captured area, the Defense Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday the ministry said 41 rebels and 16 soldiers were
killed in the offensive against the rebel-controlled territory. On
Monday it said the bodies of 86 rebels were recovered.
</P>
<P>
Government troops began the offensive in May and said it had
captured more than 100 square kilometers of land in the Wanni
area.
</P>
<P>
The ministry added that nine Tamil rebels were killed in two
other clashes on Monday in Sri Lanka's north and east.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been battling the Sri Lankan government
since 1983 for a separate homeland for minority Tamils in the
north and east of the country. 
</P>
