<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Software Exports Increase by 68 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- India's software exports grew by
68 percent in terms of rupee value during the financial year of
1998-99, touching 109.4 billion rupees (2.65 billion U.S.
dollars), out of a total revenue of 158.9 billion rupees (3.84
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to an annual survey of the National Association of
Software and Service Companies (Nasscom), the results of which
were released on Monday, the industry recorded an overall growth
of 58 percent in the year.
</P>
<P>
The emergence of information technology (IT) in the national
agenda led to the announcement of their own IT policies by 14 of
the country's 26 state governments, thus strengthening the
software industry considerably, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
At the present growth pace, Nasscom President Dewang Mehta
predicted, the export of software and services would account for
25 percent of the country's total trade in the next five years
from the current 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Y2K (year 2000) solution products accounted for 20 percent of
the software exports, Mehta said, adding that more than 90 percent
of the companies doing Y2K work have already started retraining
their staff and re-focusing on e-commerce, IT-enabled services and
interactive integration solutions.
</P>
<P>
Mehta said research and development spending of software
companies went up to 3.2 percent of their total expenditure from
2.5 percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the share of offshore software
development increased to 41 percent of the total exports.
</P>
<P>
It said the current market capitalization of the software
industry has exceeded 1 trillion rupees (approximately 23.8
billion dollars), or about 10 percent of India's gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
Five Indian companies -- Motorola India, Wipro, Satyam, ICIL
and TCS -- have obtained the highly-coveted quality certification
standard, the SEI-COMM Level 5, this year. Only five other
companies in the world have this distinction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
