<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stressing Economical Exploitation of Mineral Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- China will adopt a series of
preferential policies to encourage the use of new and advanced
technologies in its exploitation of mineral resources, according
to an official with China's Ministry of Land and Resources.
</P>
<P>
Science and technology will become an essential part of how
China protects and develops its natural resources, Vice-Minister
Jiang Chengsong said here recently.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that China is currently facing the rapid
depletion of mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
Some 168 minerals thus far discovered in the country fulfill
demand for the nation's industrial development, but 16 of the 45
strategic minerals required to ensure smooth national economic
development will be subject to depletion prior to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The total number of adequate resources is expected to drop to
23 minerals by 2010 and fall even further to six in 2020,
according to other sources.
</P>
<P>
To change the current situation, the ministry has decided to
halt its approval of any new projects on the exploitation of rare
earth, wolfram, tin and stibium from now until the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the ministry will also stop issuing
licenses to any new small or medium-sized miners of coal,
molybdenum, barite and fluorite.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
