reporters Monday that the projected meeting would tackle means of
reactivating the peace talks on all tracks, the Arabic Al-Ahram
daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
El-Sherif made the remarks after Mubarak delivered a speech to
leaders of the U.S. Jewish organizations during his ongoing visit
in Washington, the pro-government newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
El-Sherif was accompanying Mubarak in the six-day visit
starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Moderate Barak, leader of Israel's Labor Party, was elected
prime minister in the May 17 elections. He is close to forming a
broad-based coalition. He has to submit his government list to the
Knesset (parliament) by July 9.
</P>
<P>
On economic cooperation with Israel, el-Sherif quoted Mubarak
as telling the Jewish leaders that peace and normalization of
relations can never be achieved upon governments' directives. They
are nurtured in an atmosphere of confidence and security, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that Egypt is keen on realizing a just
and comprehensive peace in the Middle East, which he said would
bring the long-awaited stability and security, the national
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak called on the U.S. Jewish organizations to exert
efforts aimed at helping advance the Mideast peace process and
make peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel, plays a key role in mediating the peace talks between Arab
countries and the Jewish state. 
