<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Central Bank to Keep Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Israel has decided
to leave interest rates unchanged in July for the third month in a
row, saying it is necessary to achieve the annual inflation
target of 4 percent, local media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision by Bank of Israel Governor Jacob Frenkel to keep
the central bank's key lending rate at 12 percent came amid strong
calls from the business circle for a lower rate in order to
stimulate economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Frenkel has expressed hope that the incoming government of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak will maintain the inflation target of 4
percent and the deficit target of 2 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) set by the outgoing government of Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Defeating Netanyahu in the May elections, Barak has reached
home stretch in his process to form a coalition government. He
has not set specific economic guidelines and appointed finance
minister yet.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index (CPI) has experienced negative growth
in the first three months before rising by 0.3 percent in April,
the lowest gain in the past 35 years for the month of April.
</P>
<P>
But Frenkel said the deflation of the first four months was
only a partial correction of the unusually high CPI increases of 3
percent last fall, sparked by the international financial
turmoil, rather than a permanent new trend.
</P>
<P>
Various economic forecasts in the first few months still
predict inflation of over 4 percent this year, Frenkel said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the new government to cut expenditures and taxes,
lower deficit, conduct structural reform and invest in
infrastructure, human capital and research and development, in
order to achieve a sustainable growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Striving to Boost Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
has been working hard to maintain its position as the country's No.
1 exporter by encouraging local large companies to start up more
processing businesses abroad and sell their products overseas.
</P>
<P>
According to a local foreign trade official, the enterprises
will get much needed support in terms of capital, hard currencies
and approval procedures for going abroad if they will establish
processing workshops abroad where domestically supplied raw
materials and semi-finished products will be used in the
production.
</P>
<P>
By now, 36 large conglomerates in Guangdong have established
such overseas businesses and the products they produce are sold
abroad, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province remained the country's largest exporter last
year, but the export volume of the province dropped 17.8 percent
in the first four months of this year, though the fall off is
slowing down month by month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
