<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The arsons and looting of Serbs' houses, and acts of
violence and reprisal made by the ethnic Albanian gangs are
forcing the Kosovo Peacekeeping Force (KFOR) to play the role of
policemen and take emergency measures. In Pristina and other
regions of Kosovo, groups of Albanians claiming themselves to be
members of the Kosovo Liberation Army are suspected to have been
inflicting violence upon the Serb minority and Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
-- India and Pakistan have been engaged in a war of words and
diplomacy after New Delhi has refused to hold talks with Pakistan
without a withdrawal of Pakistani troops who India said have
infiltrated into the India-controlled part of Kashmir. Indian
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee has admitted the difficulties
met by Indian troops in the seven-week conflict in Kashmir and
said Indian troops do not intend to cross the line of control into
the Pakistani side of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The Algerian government is ready to pardon thousands of
Islamists and their sympathizers, while a draft law on "civil
harmony" is being discussed by the government ministers to define
the conditions for the release from jail or the reduction of jail
sentences of Islamists. The new law also predicts "an exemption
from legal pursuit" of all the Islamists who are not involved in
crimes of killing and rape.
</P>
<P>
-- As a sign of internal troubles of Corsica's nationalist
groups calling for independence from France, two nationalist
groups held their separate press conferences Sunday night. While
the traditional nationalist group FLNC-Historical appealed for
union of Corsicans, a previously unknown group called "Armato
Corsa" held its first nightly guerrilla-style press conference and
announced its radical platform. 
</P>
