<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects British-Dutch Proposal on Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz dismissed a draft resolution by Britain and the Netherlands
to the U.N. Security Council on the Iraqi issue as "dubious."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Al-Jazeera Satellite Channel Monday
evening, Aziz said the proposal was intended to reforge the
Security Council resolutions in a manner worse than previous
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the Netherlands recently proposed to the Security
Council that the U.N. sanctions on Iraq be suspended after Iraq
fully cooperates with an enlarged body of weapons inspectors, which
will replace the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) and carry out
more intrusive inspections on Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The purpose behind such a draft resolution is to set the stage
for a legitimate stand in the Security Council justifying a
forthcoming aggression on Iraq and putting new restrictions on Iraq
which Iraq can not abide by, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a kind of ill-fated legitimacy to launch a fresh
aggression on Iraq will emerge on the grounds that Iraq fails to
implement Security Council resolutions, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Iraq's cooperation with the Security Council on
disarmament, Aziz said that all requirements of disarmament under
U.N. resolution 687 have been fully implemented in essence and
detail.
</P>
<P>
On Iraq's delivery of document on its armaments program, Aziz
said there was an opinion prevailing in the Security Council that
since 1995 Iraq has fulfilled the essential objectives in
disarmament issues.
</P>
<P>
Aziz stressed Iraq's legitimate right to demand the lifting of
U.N. sanctions imposed on the country following its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, Aziz lashed out against the UNSCOM in
charge of disarming Iraq, saying it aimed to keep embargo in place
and fabricate pretexts for spying on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made it clear that Iraq did not expel UNSCOM, whose
weapons inspectors left Iraq last December before the U.S. and
Britain launched airstrikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"There is no justification (for the UNSCOM) to come back after
they committed an aggression on Iraq and chairman of the
commission (Richard) Butler himself was colluding with the
aggressors and knew well that the aggression would take place,"
said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about the recent detente in Iranian-Gulf
relations mainly with Saudi Arabia, Aziz said "We wish that the
relations among all the region's countries to be normal based on
international law and good neighborly relations."
</P>
<P>
On the country's current situation, Aziz said there is no
option for Iraq rather than steadfastness and adherence to
national and patriotic principles and values whatsoever the
sacrifices are.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq will remain steadfast and will never surrender despite
blackmail practiced against it through hatching conspiracies and
embargo," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
