<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary At 0800 GMT, June 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Chile will seek a solution to the Pinochet
case with every effort and means, Chile's President Eduardo Frei
told Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar here Monday.
</P>
<P>
8Frei said that his country "will search for every solution, be
it political, juridical or humanitarian."
</P>
<P>
Frei has tried to obtain Pinochet's freedom, arguing that
Garzon's request violates Chile's sovereignty because foreign
courts have no jurisdiction over its ex-leaders.
</P>
<P>
But Aznar accepted a court ruling that the request is legal. (
Chile-Pinochet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The South American Common Market (Mercosur)
and the European Union (EU) agreed on Monday to start negotiations
in November on establishing a free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique, the parties said they will define in
next November the structure, methodology and calendar of
negotiations for a progressive free trade.
</P>
<P>
The parties said that the development of free trade between
Mercosur, Chile and the EU will invigorate their relations and
strengthen the multilateral trade system.
</P>
<P>
Both blocs envisage an establishment of a free trade zone by
the year 2004 or 2005. (Mercosur-EU-Free trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia on Sunday asked the United Nations
Security Council to meet and discuss the implementation of the U.N.
resolution on Kosovo by its mission in the war-battered province.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the council, Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin
Jovanovic urged the U.N. mission to take measures to guarantee a
normal daily life for Kosovo residents, restore power supplies and
introduce a unified currency and economic system in Kosovo,
Jovanovic said. (Yugoslavia-UN-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The recent visit by Czech President Vaclav Havel to
Kosovo without the consent of Yugoslav government has violated the
basic norms governing international relations, a spokesman of the
Yugoslav foreign ministry said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The visit constitutes an act of interference in the internal
affairs of a sovereign and independent state, the spokesman said
in a statement to Tanjug, the Yugoslav news agency.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Havel's act is not acceptable and should
be condemned. (Yugoslavia-Czech-Kosovo)  
</P>
</TEXT>
