<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Grows High-Yield Paddy Rice on Desert (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese agronomists have developed
a new technique which promotes the growth of high-yield paddy rice
on boundless stretches of desert.
</P>
<P>
The new technique was introduced to a 4,000-ha experimental
zone on the Badain Jaran Desert which borders on north China's
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and Gansu Province in the
northwest.
</P>
<P>
The technique involves lining 20-centimeter deep furrows with
plastic film for preserving both water and nutrient. Rice
seedlings are then planted on a 20-30 centimeter mounds of sand
filling the furrows.
</P>
<P>
The agronomists have also developed specialized seed breeding,
planting and field management techniques in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In this way, farmers have harvested 15 tons of rice from each
hectare of the land at Badain Jaran Desert, the third largest of
its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
"Growing crops on plastic film can save 60-80 percent of
available desert water and the per hectare yield there is anything
between 1,500 and 3,000 kg more than in ordinary farmland,"
according to Xiao Honglang, a research fellow with the Lanzhou
Desert Institute under the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Foreign desert specialists describe the method as "an
innovative approach for desert reclamation".
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program (UNDP) has praised China
's desert development efforts and presented China with the "Best
Practices Award" on the World Desertification and Drought
Prevention Day which fell on June 17.
</P>
<P>
Japanese agronomists of the Tokyo University of Agriculture are
preparing to introduce the method to a desert cultivation base in
northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Xiao said the fact that desert farming requires substantially
more inputs than traditional agriculture is offset by greater
profits. He also noted a 1:5 cost-profit ratio for cash crops.
</P>
<P>
Higher initial investment cost of an average 15,000 yuan per
hectare is offset by the fact that the plastic sheeting can be
used for five years and irrigation cost can be reduced by between
33-66 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Grows High-Yield Paddy Rice on Desert (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He also noted such rice is not contaminated due to pollution-
free environment and there are few cases of harmful insects in
desert areas.
</P>
<P>
Deserts currently cover approximately 16 percent of China's
total territory.
</P>
<P>
Wang Gang, a professor with the Dry-Land Farming Laboratory
attached to Lanzhou University, described the technique as "a
nutrient box" for the paddy rice seedlings. "Promoting the
technique in China's vast desert areas will prove highly
beneficial," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The technique has been introduced to 30,000 ha of desert in
north China's Inner Mongolia, Shaanxi and Gansu provinces and the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in the northwest. Approximately
half of the desert area has paid off economically in various ways.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the technique can be used on condition of having
water sources, either surface or underground water.
</P>
<P>
The Lanzhou Desert Institute has trained 200 technicians and
currently developing a more extensive training program as the
application of water in such desert areas calls for management
expertise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
