<HEADLINE> Multilateral Forum on Mideast Peace Expected Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A multilateral forum is expected to
open next week in Cairo in a bid to seek ways of reviving the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian, Jordanian and Israeli delegations will meet in the
three-day event, to be opened by Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa, the English-language paper said.
</P>
<P>
Former Egyptian Prime Minister Mustapha Khalil will chair the
forum.
</P>
<P>
Invited to the opening ceremony are Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres and
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
The gathering is expected to send a message to Israeli Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak, calling on him to step up efforts aimed
at pushing the peace drive forward, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks made little progress in the past
three years due to the intransigent policies of Barak's hardline
predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Barak's victory in the May 17 elections has raised hopes for
the revival of the peace process as he pledged to embrace a
moderate stand on the negotiations with Israel's Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Before and after his election, Barak promised to advance the
peacemaking with the Palestinians and resume the negotiations with
Syria and Lebanon which have been in a stalemate since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan, the only two Arab countries that have sealed
peace treaties with the Jewish state, are key mediators in the
peace drive, along with the U.S., one of the co-sponsors of the
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
