<HEADLINE> PKK Leader Ocalan Sentenced to Death in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Ankara State Security
Court Tuesday sentenced Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), to death for treason.
</P>
<P>
The court gave Ocalan the death penalty as he "betrayed the
country."
</P>
<P>
The court said that it decided to sentence Ocalan to capital
punishment under Article 125 of Turkish Penal Code.
</P>
<P>
The article says that "the person who commits an act to bring a
part or whole of the state's territories under the hegemony of a
foreign state, or to subtract from the independence of the state,
or to disrupt the unity, or to separate some part of the
territories under the sovereignty of the state, will be punished
with death sentence."
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was captured by Turkish special agents in Kenya in
mid-February and detained on Imrali Island in Marmara Sea near
western Turkey's province of Bursa for trials on charges of
treason and separatism.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan-led PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an
independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts
between the the government troops and PKK rebels have claimed
over 37,000 lives and the government held Ocalan responsible for
the deaths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICC Urges WTO Members to Launch New Round of Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Chamber of
Commerce (ICC) has called on the World Trade Organization (WTO)
members to launch a new round of negotiations on trade
liberalization and to finish the talks within three years.
</P>
<P>
In a press release Tuesday, the Paris-based ICC said that the
timing is right for a decision on the new round to be made at the
WTO ministerial conference scheduled in Seattle at the end of
November.
</P>
<P>
The ICC believed that a new broad-based round of talks would "
make a significant contribution to restoring confidence in the
prospects for the recovery of the world economy in the wake of the
emerging markets crisis."
</P>
<P>
It proposed that WTO members set up interim deadlines and
regular progress reviews to ensure that the talks would be
concluded relatively quickly, in about three years, so as to avoid
the delays that characterized the previous Uruguay Round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
