<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Successful in HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- As Hong Kong is prepared to
celebrate the 2nd anniversary of its return to China, the
successful implementation of the principle of "one country, two
systems" is warmly acclaimed here in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Tien Pei-Chun, chairman
of the Liberal Party, said that the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland is not only a historic event for China, but also a
focus of world attention.
</P>
<P>
The great concept of 'one country, two systems' is
unprecedented in the political history of mankind, and if this
principle is successfully implemented in Hong Kong, it will
provide important experience to other people in the world in
solving their own internal political contradictions, Tien said.
</P>
<P>
"Now I can tell you with certainty that the principle of 'one
country, two systems' has had a good beginning in Hong Kong, and
this has laid a solid foundation for Hong Kong's future
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Government has strictly implemented the principle
of 'one country, two systems' and the policy of 'high degree of
autonomy', giving the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (
HKSAR) Government a free hand to handle Hong Kong's internal
affairs, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong economy has been seriously affected by the Asian
financial turmoil in the past two years. Luckily, the Central
Government has kept the exchange rate of the Chinese currency (
Renminbi) unchanged and prevented it from devaluating, thus
greatly alleviating the pressure upon Hong Kong's economy.
Moreover, as Hong Kong is now vigorously developing itself into a
knowledge-based metropolis for facing up to the challenges of the
upcoming new millennium, the mainland has given it a strong
support in respect of scientific research and science and
technology personnel.
</P>
<P>
"I am deeply convinced that in the new millennium, the world
people will all the more endorse the success of the 'one country,
two systems' principle and approve Chinese leaders' far-
sightedness. I am even more convinced that both Hong Kong and
Macao will develop better under the principle of 'one country, two
systems'," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his interview with Xinhua, professor Li Kwok Cheung, vice-
chancellor of the Chinese University of Hong Kong and also an
influential figure in Hong Kong's educational circles, said that
people may ask whether education and academic freedom are
guaranteed in Hong Kong two years after its return to China. "As a
member of the educational circles, my answer is definitely yes,"
he stated.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, after the return, university education in Hong Kong
has developed more comprehensively, and academic exchanges with
the inland areas, in particular, have become more frequent," he
said, adding that "academic research freedom is still respected
and all academic views can be aired freely."
</P>
<P>
We can likewise say that 'one country, two systems' principle
has also been well implemented in regard to education and academic
freedom, he stated.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong has given it a good opportunity to
disseminate the Chinese culture to the rest of the world, enabling
Hong Kong to more positively develop the Chinese culture by making
a direct use of its features and advantages and further promote
China's opening and the exchanges between Chinese and foreign
cultures. As time goes on, such a role of Hong Kong will become
even more clear, he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Successful in HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The success of the principle of
'one country, two systems' is also manifested in the spheres of
freedom, rule of law and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Member of Hong Kong's Executive Council and Legislative Council
Tan Yiu Chung told Xinhua that due to protection by the Basic Law,
no restrictions have been imposed on these aspects and the
atmosphere in these spheres has become even more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
This is particularly true in the freedom of press, he said,
adding that there are no differences whatsoever between now and
the pre-return period. There are even some cases in which press
freedom has been somewhat abused. However the HKSAR Government has
never interfered, leaving it for the press circles to solve all by
itself through self-regulation.
</P>
<P>
Lawful mass parades and gatherings are never subject to any
restrictions. Citizens can sue the government in court whenever
they have complaints and such cases are numerous since the return
and the court has dealt with the cases all independently.
</P>
<P>
Apart from his routine work, he said, he usually takes two or
three nights out of his schedule every week going down to the
grass-roots levels and the people there are all happy to air their
opinions and he can reflect their views in good time at the
Executive Council meetings.
</P>
<P>
Tsang Yok Sing, chairman of the Democratic Alliance for the
Betterment of Hong Kong and member of the Legislative Council,
said that the majority of Hong Kong people and foreigners in Hong
Kong agree that the basic rights of Hong Kong people, their
freedom and the rule of law have been guaranteed since the return
of Hong Kong to China. Some people had held the pessimistic view
that there would be no human rights and rule of law after the
return.
</P>
<P>
"Facts have shown that such a view does not hold any water
because it is groundless," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"In fact Hong Kong people are now enjoying more rights than
some people had predicted," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of democracy, Tsang cited the election of HKSAR's
first Legislative Council last year as an example, saying that it
was conducted throughout in accordance with the methods stipulated
by the Basic Law and that the voters' turnout rate was higher than
any such elections before Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
The process of examining and discussing the large number of
bills and government policies has also fully manifested the spirit
of democracy, he said, quoting from his personal experience. Some
powers which were concentrated in the hands of the government
during British colonial rule are now being gradually deregulated.
For instance, while the former Hong Kong British governments were
always free from some rules and regulations, the HKSAR Government,
following the changes after the return, has conscientiously
subjected itself to the rule of law in all its performances and
the Central Government's organs stationed in Hong Kong also do the
same, he commented.
</P>
<P>
That the principle of 'one country, two systems' and the policy
of Hong Kong people ruling Hong Kong have been well implemented
was a point particularly emphasized by Fung Kwok King, chairman of
Hong Kong Trade Development Council, in a recent interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"This is not only seen by Hong Kong people themselves, but also
approved by chambers of commerce of various countries in Hong Kong
and the business circles the world over," he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners who are familiar with Hong Kong still hope to do
business here. What is more, since Hong Kong is part of China,
they continue to regard Hong Kong as a base for furthering their
relations with China and pay even more attention to this base, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has therefore kept its competitive edges in the past
two years since its return to China," he stated. 
</P>
