<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislature Publishes Macao Garrison Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese legislature made public
today the details of the Garrison Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
The Law was adopted yesterday during the 10th session of the
Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
The law's six chapters and 30 articles cover the general
principles, responsibilities of the People's Liberation Army
troops stationed in Macao, relations between the garrison and the
MSAR government, duties of and disciplines governing troops,
judicial jurisdiction over the garrison and supplementary articles.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates that general principles of the Garrison Law
are enacted in accordance to the Constitution and the Basic Law of
the Macao Special Administrative Region in order to guarantee the
forces stationed in the region are able to fulfill their duties
and safeguard the sovereignty, territorial integrity and unity of
the nation, as well as protect the security of the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
Forces stationed in the region will not interfere into local
affairs. The government of the MSAR will, however, have the right
to request that the Central Government issue orders instructing
the garrison to help maintain social security or provide disaster
relief when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Macao garrison will abide by both the laws of
China and the laws of the MSAR. The Central Government will cover
all expenditures required for the deployment.
</P>
<P>
The garrison's defense duties include guarding against
aggression, safeguarding security in the MSAR and managing the
military establishment in MSAR and dealing with military affairs
concerning foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The Garrison Law stipulates that the government of the MSAR
should provide support enabling the garrison to fulfill its duties
and protect the legal rights and interests of those stationed in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The law requires members of the garrison to respect
administrative organizations in the MSAR, as well the social
system and lifestyles in the region.
</P>
<P>
Nine articles in the law clearly define judicial jurisdiction
over troops stationed troops in the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
The law also stipulates that the NPC Standing Committee retains
the sole right to interpret the law.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin signed a decree on Monday
approving promulgation of the law which will enter effect on
December 20, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
