<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Donate Money for Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 29 (Xinhua) -- After Israel launched its bloodiest
air strike on Lebanon since 1996, Lebanon's all walks of life
donated money to help the cash-strapped government rebuild the
damages caused in the blitz.
</P>
<P>
The country's leading bank Byblos Bank has donated 1 million
U.S. dollars to the government for the reconstruction efforts, the
Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This donation is designed to help rebuild the power stations
and road networks that were hit by the Israeli planes," the bank
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Byblos said that the attack was aimed at destroying Lebanon's
national economy at a time when Lebanon is experiencing financial
hardships and recession.
</P>
<P>
Thursday night, Israel launched the biggest onslaught on
Lebanon since the 1996 "Grapes of Wrath" operations, killing
eight people and wounding 64.
</P>
<P>
The country's two power stations, three bridges linking the
capital to its south and a telephone relay station were also
destroyed in the attack which followed a cross-border Katyusha
barrage by guerrillas of Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed that its attack served as a retaliation for
Hezbollah's offensive which killed two Israelis while the
Iranian-backed group argued it fired rockets into northern Israel
to avenge the wounding of six Lebanese civilians in Israel's
shelling.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's central bank has opened a special account to receive
local and foreign assistance in the wake of the Israeli attacks.
</P>
<P>
The four semi-finalists in this year's Lebanese Basketball
Championship have donated 36,000 dollars which are their earnings
from the competition to help the reconstruction cause.
</P>
<P>
Billionaire Saudi Prince Walid bin Talal, whose mother is a
Lebanese, has offered to foot the bill of rebuilding the power
stations estimated at 30 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
