<HEADLINE> Wild Mandarin Ducks Visit Northeast China's Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A mandarin duck and her seven
ducklings have suddenly appeared in a park in Harbin, northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province, which is quite rare, said
zoologists.
</P>
<P>
Park staff found the ducks by accident several days ago. And Xu
Qing, zoologist in the Northeast China Forestry University,
explained that mandarin duck is a wild species which mostly lives
in valleys and near brooks.
</P>
<P>
Normally they will travel to the middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze River to spend the cold winter and return to the
northeast of China in spring for breeding. Ornithologists believe
the ducks visit this very noisy park for the clean water and the
nice environment.
</P>
<P>
The province is abundant with wild creatures and natural
resources with statistics from 1998 indicating that there are 374
species of birds, 87 sorts of wild animals and 25 kinds of
reptiles and amphibians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
