<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Sets Up FBI-style Cops to Fight Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
has formed a new high-priority crimes investigation unit, similar
to the United States' FBI, as a cornerstone of the government's
coordinated approach to fighting crime, the Star newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The blueprint, unveiled in Parliament Monday, includes:
</P>
<P>
-- A new multidisciplinary national unit to investigate
priority crimes, improvement of police skills, tough measures to
deal with police killers and a new law to control illegal
firearms.
</P>
<P>
-- Involving civil society and the South African National
Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
-- Ongoing clean-up activities in a number of flashpoints.
These include roadblocks and cordon-and-search operations.
</P>
<P>
-- A call from National Director of Public Prosecutions
Bulelani Nguka for an urgent revamp of criminal-justice
legislation which will compel defense teams to disclose their
strategy in criminal trials.
</P>
<P>
-- Formal fortnightly meetings for safety and Security Minister
Steve Tshwete, Justice Minister Penuell Maduna and Correctional
Services Minister Ben Skosana to co-ordinate the anti-crime fight.
</P>
<P>
"The new structure will focus -- with the backup of highly
skilled personnel, effective equipment and adequate resources-- on
crime- intelligence gathering and the investigation and
prosecution of individuals and groups involved in priority
crimes," Tshwete said in Parliament Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said he was confident he and other ministers involved would
be ready to brief President Thabo Mbeki before the end of next
week.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Minister Trevor Manuel was also being included in
the multidisciplinary approach and the recent two-day cabinet
meeting had unanimously agreed that something had to be done to
empower the police, Tshwete said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has been haunted by a wave of rising crimes
involving gangs and firearms. Crimes have prompted an outflow of
foreign capital, and economists warn that if crimes are not
checked, the country's economy will be further affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
