<HEADLINE> Kenya to Fully Privatize Telecom Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Government has
appointed a nine- member transitional management committee to help
wind up the delayed privatization process of state-owned giant
Kenya Posts and Telecommunications Corporation (KPTC).
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Transport and Communication Minister William Ntimama
said in the latest issue of the Kenya Gazette that the committee
would assist the corporation's board in the privatization process
and remain in office until completion, according to Tuesday's East
African Standard.
</P>
<P>
Privatization of KPTC is one of the preconditions for the
resumption of talks with the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
over its 205 million U.S. dollars loan suspended in July 1997. A
team from the IMF arrived in Kenya on June 26 for a two-week
visit.
</P>
<P>
According to the program, KPTC will be split into three
entities: Telkom Kenya Limited, Kenya Postal Corporation and the
regulatory body Communications of Kenya by June 30.
</P>
<P>
Ntimama also said that the Kenya Communications Act and the
Postal Corporation of Kenya Act, which were recently publicized,
would come into effect on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government requested this month the World Bank for a
 partial extension of a 22.3 million dollars loan to finance the
privatization of KPTC, such as providing money to the redundant
workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
