<HEADLINE> Kenya Introduces New Axle Load Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has introduced new measures
to curb overloading on roads and is ready to effectively enforce
all aspects of the Traffic Act, according to the Ministry of
Public Works.
</P>
<P>
The government has installed four mobile weigh-bridges at its
four major cities, Mombasa, Nairobi, Eldoret and Kisumu, for
transporters to weigh their vehicles before they start on their
tourney, the ministry Permanent Secretary Mohammed Isahakia said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Three weigh-bridges have also been placed at Malaba, Namanga
and Busia border stations to check all incoming and outgoing
vehicles," he added, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new measures, which become effective once a legal notice is
 published, will include the raising of the fine for overloading
from one shilling per kilogram to five shillings.
</P>
<P>
According to the measures, the maximum gross vehicle weight for
trucks will be increased from 46 tons to 54 tons and the maximum
length from current 18 meters to 22 meters.
</P>
<P>
Isahakia said his ministry officials at the weigh-bridges will
be required to issue drivers with the evidence that their
vehicles have been weighed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
