<HEADLINE> Chinese Airborne Units Conduct Training Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The People's Liberation Army (PLA)
recently conducted a massive airborne training exercise on the
Qinhai-Tibetan Plateau in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
"The successful exercise indicates that the Chinese paratroops
have had the ability to carry out an airborne mission in a region
with complicated geological conditions," according to a military
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The exercise was conducted in the mountainous Aba Prefecture,
a Tibetan inhabited area in southwest China's Sichuan Province
which is covered by snow and ice at the time of the exercise.
</P>
<P>
All paratroopers hit prescribed landing zones in spite of low
visibility due to rain, said the spokesman, adding that mock
battles were conducted in gorges, as well as on snow-covered
mountains and in swampy areas.
</P>
<P>
The exercise featured the use of new equipment and technology,
including state-of-the-art communications equipment which allows
soldiers to pinpoint their exact locations and easily communicate
with command centers immediately following their landing.
</P>
<P>
The paratroopers also used new intelligence gathering equipment
and engine-powered hang gliders to improve their operational
capabilities, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said the main goals of the exercise centered on testing new
technology and collecting data needed for future military tactics.
</P>
