<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fish Losing Environment Struggles on Upper Reaches of Yangtze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Rare fish, including the Chinese
paddlefish and mullet, are under threat as a result of the
deteriorating water environment on the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
A recent study, conducted by the Chinese Academy of Sciences'
Institute of Hydrobiology, indicated that the population of
paddlefish and mullet has decreased rapidly in recent years. And
Chinese sturgeon has now disappeared on the upper reaches of the
river.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the variety of fish in general has decreased from
over 50 in the mid-1960's to 20 odd today, said Zhang Guohua, a
doctor with the institute.
</P>
<P>
The main reasons are attributed to over-fishing, water
pollution, and water facility construction.
</P>
<P>
The habitat of the fish should be preserved in order to
protect the rare fish, experts agree. However, it is unrealistic
to ban the construction of water facilities, for the river has
electricity generation, water transportation and other important
functions, the said.
</P>
<P>
"But we can choose one or two tributaries of the river to build
nature reserves for the rare fish," said Cao Wenxuan, chairman of
the executive council of the China Fish Society, and an
academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Cao, after long studies, has suggested that the Chishui River,
a tributary of Yangtze, be very suitable for such reserves,
because it's natural environment is well preserved.
</P>
<P>
Some 109 kinds of fish, including 26 species which only live on
the upper reaches of Yangtze River, have been found there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
