<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Serious Flooding in Bangladesh This Year: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Experts here predict no serious
flooding in Bangladesh this monsoon although flash floods have hit
the country's southeastern greater Chittagong region following
several days of downpour.
</P>
<P>
"If anything abnormal doesn't happen...if everything goes as
predicted both in Bangladesh and India, we can hope that we won't
have to face another calamity (as that of last year),"
Meteorological Department Director Ershad Hossain said, The
Financial Express reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Similar views were expressed by Dr. Anwar Ali, chairman of the
Bangladesh Space Research and Remote Sensing Organization. He said
the current spell of downpour that caused flash floods mainly in
the hill districts it would continue hardly for one or two days.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Flood Forecasting and Warning Center (FFWC)
said all the rivers in the Southeastern hill basin marked fall and
were flowing below the danger levels on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But water levels of most rivers covering the major districts
hit by the century's worst floods last year marked rise on Monday.
Sharif M. Rafiqul Islam, executive engineer at the Water
Development Board who is in charge of the FFWC, said there was no
need to be worried as next week's predictions didn't have
indication of floods.
</P>
<P>
"Water levels in the Ganges basin are still far below the
danger levels. Rivers in the Brahmaputra basin may cross the
danger levels only at one or two points which is not uncommon at
this moment," he said.
</P>
<P>
About the floods in the Chittagong region, he said flash floods
in the hills were a common phenomenon and the areas this season
already experienced one. "So, another flood in the three hill
districts is not being apprehended," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was badly hit by a prolonged flood last year, which
lasted from July to September, affecting two-thirds of the country
and inflicting an estimated loss of 4.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
