<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Steel Giants to Merge to Cut Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's four major producers of
iron and steel for construction are expected to sign a memorandum
of understanding to merge their operation in order to cut costs,
the Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The four companies, namely Siam Cement Plc, Nakornthai Stripped
Mill (NTS), Bangkok Steel Industry Plc (BSI) and Nam Heang Group,
collectively control more than half of the local market.
</P>
<P>
The plan, proposed by U.S.-based consultant McDonald Investment
and Securities, is aimed at ensuring the survival of the
companies, which are ridden with debts totaling between 2 billion
and 2.2 billion U.S. dollars, by cutting their production costs to
cope with a 40-percent slump in demand over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
The sharp decline in the construction sector means that the
companies are operating at only 30 percent of iron and steel
production capacity, well below viable economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
Against a combined capacity of 8 million tons, the four managed
to produce only 3 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Siam Cement will be the largest shareholder of the combined
entity since its two steel rod makers will be merged with the
three steel rod units of NTS, BSI and Nam Heang.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post quoted local industry experts as saying that
the merger is not intended to create a domestic monopoly or a
national cartel to compete with foreign countries, but to survive
the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
By working together, the producers would have stronger
negotiating power with supplies of raw materials and customers
abroad, the experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0257 </DOCNO>
