<HEADLINE> Thailand Moves to Lift Ban on Belgian Foodstuff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Officials of Thailand's
Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperative Ministry have been
instructed to consider lifting the ban on imported foodstuff from
Belgium, The Nation reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move was the result of a meeting between Agriculture
Minister Pongpol Adireksarn and Belgian Ambassador Christina
Funes-Noppen on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Thai minister, Belgium has given an assurance
that ingredients of animal feed imported by Thailand after June
12, are not dioxin-contaminated.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian side confirmed that feed ingredients imported after
June 12 have been tested and proved to contain no dioxin.
</P>
<P>
Those which were imported prior to that date will be checked
and certified as safe if proved to be free from the chemical.
</P>
<P>
Another reason which makes the Thai minister issue an order to
departments concerned to consider lifting the ban is the mounting
fear among local businessmen that the ban may affect foreign
investment in the country and Thai workers. 
</P>
