<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, June 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Wall Street stocks moved higher Monday as investors
were convinced that the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates
by only a quarter percentage point at its meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
 The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 102.59 at 10,655.
15. The index lost 303 points last week.
</P>
<P>
 Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 16.04 at 1,331.35 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq index rose 49.79 at 2,602.44. (US-Wall Street-Closing)
</P>
<P>
 - - - -
</P>
<P>
 RIO DE JANEIRO -- The South American Common Market (Mercosur)
and the European Union (EU) agreed on Monday to start negotiations
in November on establishing a free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
The commitment was made during a meeting between the heads of
State or government of Mercosur (made up of Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay), Chile and EU countries, except Britain.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique, the parties said they will define in
next November the structure, methodology and calendar of
negotiations for a progressive free trade. (Mercosur-EU-Free
trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ZAGREB -- Croatia on Monday urged the World Bank to provide it
with loans for the clearance of more than one million landmines
deployed in the country during the civil war in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Jaranka Kosor, deputy speaker of the Croatian Parliament, made
the appeal in a speech to an international meeting on landmines
which opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kosor said Croatia needs some two billion dollars to clear all
landmines used in the civil war which erupted following the
disintegration of the former Yugoslavia. (Croatia-Aid-Landmine)
</P>
<P>
