<HEADLINE> Farmers Continue Protest in Croatia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Croatia continued their
protest Monday, demanding that the government stop importing
agricultural products and protect their interests, local press
reports said.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 farmers placed road blocks in more than 30
places in northern Croatia and Slavonija as well as several border
paths leading to Slovenia, Hungary and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
As many as 12,000-15,000 farmers, who started their protests
last Saturday, blocked the roads with tractors and trucks in seven
out of 21 prefectures and asked to hold a dialogue with the
government.
</P>
<P>
They demand that the government ban import of agricultural
products until surplus domestic products are purchased. Besides
they demand that government pay back the money owned to them and
increase the wheat price from 1.1 kuna to 1.32 kuna per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the farmers' union held a talk with the government,
but the two sides did not reach any agreement.
</P>
<P>
Croatian Prime Minister Zlatko Matesa said that the farmers'
protest was illegal, causing the government great difficulties to
carry out its functions.
</P>
<P>
However, Matesa said, the government would not use force to
forbid the farmers from protesting.
</P>
<P>
Following the failure in the talks, union leaders said they
would organize protests on a larger scale, the reports said.
</P>
</TEXT>
