<HEADLINE> Latin America, EU to Be Partners: Brazilian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 28 (Xinhua)-- Brazilian President Fernando
Cardoso on Monday called on the countries in Latin America, the
Caribbean region and the European Union (EU) to cooperate with
orientation toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
While inaugurating Rio Summit among the heads of state or
government from Latin America, the Caribbean and the EU, Cardoso
said "Let us be partners in the fascinating project that already
belongs to the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
"We are living at a moment in which the international system is
undergoing unprecedented transformations in political, economic,
social and technological fields," said the Brazilian president.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso pointed out that "globalization must be open for all.
It cannot be a present for the rich with the poor neglected. To
transform an asymmetrical globalization into a common
globalization is a question of justice and democratic aspiration."
</P>
<P>
Leaders from 48 nations who attended the two-day summit will
discuss the date for future negotiations on creating a free-trade
zone among Latin America, the Caribbean and the EU, according to
sources present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The trade zone is expected to be in place in 2004 or 2005.
</P>
