<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Destroys Over 3,900 Hectares Poppy Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar authorities destroyed a
total of 3,979 hectares of poppy fields scattered in the country's
Shan and Kachin states and Mandalay division in 1998-99 opium
cultivation season from November 1998 up to May 1999, official
newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There is a total of 61,236 hectares of poppy cultivation area
in the country with an annual opium production of 665.28 tons
which could be refined into 66.52 tons of heroin.
</P>
<P>
In its opium eradication efforts, Myanmar has been carrying out
cultivation of poppy-substitute crops in areas where poppy was
planted.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the cultivation area of the poppy substitute crops
such as sugarcane, jute, rubber and buckwheat stood at 5,898
hectares and it has planned to cultivate 4,916 hectares of such
crops in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Due to the expanded cultivation area of these substitute crops,
the production of drug and its supply are dropping.
</P>
<P>
Beginning this year, the Myanmar government has been
implementing a 15-year plan for total opium eradication following
the declaration of Mongla region in eastern Shan state as an
"Opium-Free Zone" in April 1997, and the plan implementation has
been started in the priority areas of 51 townships under the
first five-year project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Trading to Go Public in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Provincial government recently instructed every county and city in
the province to replace the existing land-use transfer and lease
practices with public trading by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Zheng, director of the Guangdong Land Resource Department,
explained that the new market mechanism will help avoid "under-the-
table" land-use transfers.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, a pioneer in China's reform in land use, had either
leased or transferred land-use rights to over 40.9 percent of its
total available land by the end of last year. The province also
witnessed the emergence of small land-use trade markets in various
cities.
</P>
<P>
However, Yuan pointed out ineffective regulation of the markets
has led to complaints and lawsuits involving illegal land deals,
as well as tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
"The market, instead of the government, will control land-use
transfers in the future," according to Yuan.
</P>
<P>
The local government expects the new land-use markets to
promote the effective use of idle land resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
