<HEADLINE> Czech Peacekeeping Troops Head for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PROSTEJOV, The Czech Republic, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A train
loaded with the first 30 Czech peacekeeping troops left here
Monday afternoon for Kosovo, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The troops, coming from the sixth scout company of the Czech
army, will conduct peacekeeping missions in the British-controled
sector of Kosovo after they arrive there via the Slovak Republic,
Hungary, Romania and Macedonia, according to the head of the
forces.
</P>
<P>
The second batch of forces will set off by train early Tuesday
morning along the same route.
</P>
<P>
Under a bill passed by the parliament June 15, the Czech
Republic will send a total of 800 troops to the war-ridden
Yugoslav province for a period of 18 months or longer in
accordance with circumstances there.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo was divided into five peacekeeping sectors dominated
separately by the United States, Britain, France, Italy and
Germany under an agreement reached between NATO and Yugoslav
generals at the end of NATO's 78-day bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
