<HEADLINE> U.N. Urged to Review Implementation of Kosovo Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia on Sunday asked the
United Nations Security Council to meet and discuss the
implementation of the U.N. resolution on Kosovo by its mission in
the war-battered province.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the council, Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin
Jovanovic urged the U.N. mission to "unrelentingly" implement the
U.N. resolution and fully guarantee the safety of all ethnic
groups in Kosovo and their properties.
</P>
<P>
The minister also asked the U.N. mission to prevent all forms
of violence and terrorism in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has fully fulfilled its obligations set in the U.N.
resolution and the council should keep up its commitments, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav government hopes that the U.N. mission will take
measures to guarantee a normal daily life for Kosovo residents,
restore power supplies and introduce a unified currency and
economic system in Kosovo, Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace agreement, the United Nations will run Kosovo's
civilian administration while NATO commands the peacekeeping force
in the province.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Serbs have reportedly fled Kosovo for
fear of revenge by Albanian refugees returning to the province.
</P>
<P>
There have been repeated reports of vengeance attacks by ethnic
Albanians on Serbs remaining in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
