<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Economy Seen to Pick Up in Second Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's economy is expected to
pick up in the second half of this year with a growth of 4 percent
despite the deteriorating external environment, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit will also be contained to 7.8 percent of the
gross domestic product (GDP) this year against 9.2 percent in
1998, the official Daily News Tuesday quoted Deputy Secretary to
the Treasury Dr. P.B. Jayasundara as saying.
</P>
<P>
"While we know there is an economic slowdown largely due to
external factors, the economy fundamentally remains stable,"
Jayasundara said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's GDP in real terms grew by 2.7 percent during the
first quarter of this year compared to 5.7 percent in the
corresponding period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Private sector analysts have forecast a GDP growth of below 4
percent this year and a deficit higher than that of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor A.S. Jayawardena has said that based on
the first quarter GDP growth, the bank was estimating a 4-percent
growth for 1999. Early this year, a growth rate between 4 percent
to 4.5 percent was forecast.
</P>
<P>
Jayasundera believed that the economy will pick up for the
better during the last two quarters and negate any downfall of the
first half, given an analysis of the economic performance in the
first five months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Tea prices were stabilizing, the livestock sector output was
buoyant, and the services sector was vibrant and the manufacturing
sector was also managing well, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
