<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks in Tianjin Show Strong Performance (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Tianjin Branch of China's
central bank, has recently released statistics showing that 13 of
25 foreign financial institutions in the northern port city makes
a profit.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBOC) release shows that profits
for related institutions grew by 27 percent to 15.72 million US
dollars in 1998 in spite of the adverse impact of the Asian
Financial Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for May show total net profits for all foreign banks
in Tianjin hit 7.35 million U.S. dollars, up 46.4 percent on April.
</P>
<P>
The volume of foreign funds flowing into the major financial
center in north China over the past few years has prompted a
number of financial institutions from the United States, Japan,
the Republic of Korea (ROK), Britain, France, Singapore and Hong
Kong to expand operations. Total assets for related institutions
have grown 20-fold on 1993 to over 2.4 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Feng, director of the Tianjin branch's administration for
foreign financial organizations, attributes the success to the
business flexibility of said institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment Confidence Returns to Emerging Markets: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Corporations around the world
are increasing their foreign direct investment as they acknowledge
more stable global economic conditions, according to a report
released Monday by a U.S. consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
Confidence in the global investment environment has risen over
the past six months, said the semi-annual survey of top executives
of Global 1000 companies conducted by A.T. Kearney, one of the
world's largest management consulting firms. The firm's foreign
direct investment index compares the relative likelihood of direct
investment in 60 countries over the next one to three years.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the firm said, 33 percent of senior executives
surveyed indicate a more positive outlook than six months ago and
75 percent plan to maintain or slightly increase their investments
abroad. In particular, Japanese corporate investors are more
likely to invest abroad today than they were six months ago.
</P>
<P>
After two years of instability in emerging markets, Brazil's
decision to devalue its currency early this year did not lead to
further system-wide breakdown. As a result, the report said, fears
that the emerging market crisis inexorably would become global
have subsided.
</P>
<P>
Unlike in last December, when the greatest concern for
executives was the future of emerging markets, the report said,
the focus now has shifted to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Today, 87 percent of respondents say their greatest concern is
whether U.S. economic growth will remain robust enough to continue
fueling global recovery and driving the investment outlook
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The United States remains the most attractive investment
destination, with 40 percent of corporations surveyed saying that
they are highly likely to invest in this market.
</P>
<P>
Investors continue to be cautious about Japan, as 85 percent of
the executives worldwide say that Japanese recession is adversely
affecting their investment plans.
</P>
<P>
While corporate confidence in Europe and Latin America has
waned over the past six months, Asia as a whole is relatively more
attractive than six months ago.
</P>
<P>
China is now second only to the United States as the most
preferred investment destination, taking the number two ranking
previously held by Brazil. But according to the survey, although
China is also ranked as the most attractive emerging market
worldwide, China's overall attractiveness to investors has
deteriorated. Twenty-seven percent of executives surveyed consider
China's outlook more negative than six months ago.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, 51 percent of senior executives investing Asia
indicate that the Asian crisis has created acquisition
opportunities for their firms. South Korea appears to be the main
beneficiary of this trend.  
</P>
</TEXT>
