<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks in Tianjin Shows Strong Performance (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign financial institutions manage their business affairs in
accordance with international practices and quickly recognize
potentially profitable areas. They have abandoned the former
practice of focusing solely on enterprises from their own country
and have substantially increased loans to China's state-owned
enterprises, with the total loan volume for 1998 hitting 165
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Managers of foreign banks note that efficient supervision and
administration in China has not only helped foreign financial
institutions reduce risk, but has also created a good environment
for earning profits.
</P>
<P>
China's financial departments have not only issued explicit
regulations and laws, but also conducts regular audits of foreign-
funded financial organization to prevent any potential dangers and
problems.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that foreign-funded financial organizations have a
bright future in China and will benefit from the nation's
sustainable development and economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
PBOC statistics show that 89 foreign financial institutions
from 21 countries and regions had established 178 branches in
various cities in China by the end of 1998, with an additional 164
foreign banks from 38 countries and regions opening representative
offices.
</P>
<P>
Foreign financial institutions were previously allowed to
operate in only 23 cities and Hainan Province, However, the PBOC's
decisions in January this year allowing them to conduct business
activities in all major cities throughout the nation and conduct
Renminbi transactions on a trial basis have encouraged further
development of China's financial market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
