<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Denies Tax Fraud Allegations by Swiss Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic Committee
denied on Monday in Lausanne it had been involved in any form of
tax fraud and falsification of documents.
</P>
<P>
"It's not true," IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said,
referring to the allegations made last week by a Swiss magazine. "
It's as simple as that."
</P>
<P>
The Lausanne weekly L'Hebdo printed what it said was a secret
Swiss government memorandum describing the alleged IOC misconduct.
</P>
<P>
The magazine claimed that Swiss authorities had not taken
action because the Swiss town Sion had been campaigning for the
2006 Winter Games then. The IOC finally chose Italy's Turin.
</P>
<P>
Servan-Schreiber said the IOC had an unwritten agreement with
local Vaud state authorities, dating back to 1971, that exempted
foreign workers from tax on 30 percent of earnings and Swiss
employees from tax on 15 percent of earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
