<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Some European Firms Do Well Than Others in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey shows that most
European companies in China are doing well and believe that their
performance will improve significantly within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Fiducia Co. Ltd. under the
sponsorship of the Delegation of the European Commission in
Beijing, looks into the situation of European investment in China
and the reasons why some companies are more successful than others,
according to Tuesday's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Only 11 percent of the companies surveyed felt unsatisfied, and
among the rest of the well-doing ones the joint ventures turned
out to be more successful than wholly owned ones, the survey
indicates.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that those successful companies in China
provide the domestic market with products of the same quality as
in Europe, and that they use local raw materials and semi-finished
products to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, successful companies have also spent more time
visiting China before establishing a business, conducted more
market tests than unsuccessful companies, and made good use of
market surveys, especially those concerning potential demand and
competition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Policy Should Focus on Better Livelihood: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The central government's policy of
expanding domestic demand should aim at not only preventing
economic recession but, more importantly, improving people's
living standards, a leading Chinese economist says.
</P>
<P>
Among all the development goals, job creation should top the
agenda of both the central and local governments, Hu Angang, a
researcher with the Chinese Academy of Sciences, says.
</P>
<P>
Hu makes the suggestion in an article published in today's
China Daily, which calls for "fundamental changes" in orientation
of economic policies.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, China's employment situation has failed to keep
up with the country's rapid economic growth, Hu says.
</P>
<P>
China's workforce amounts to 26.3 percent of the world's total,
but its capital resources is just 3.4 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, China's economic growth should help
create more jobs, he says, adding that in the short term, it
should try to keep the unemployment rate to be between five and
six percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, reform of the social welfare system, including
workers' pension insurance, unemployment insurance and medical
insurance, should precede the reform of state-owned enterprises,
because the success of the latter to a large extent hinges on the
former, he says.
</P>
<P>
He suggests that the state make bold reforms in areas
applicable to the general populace in fields such as
telecommunications and higher education.
</P>
<P>
While boosting efficiency-oriented economic growth, the
government should also adhere to the principle of fairness in
providing public services such as elementary education, public
health, family planning and, with special reference to rural areas,
ensuring the supply of clean drinking water and making power more
affordable, he says.
</P>
<P>
Due to insufficient funds, unemployment support payments are
very low and differ greatly among regions, Hu says, noting that
some enterprises are already in arrears in paying pensions and
salaries.
</P>
<P>
These deficiencies constitute a serious threat to the country's
social stability, Hu says.
</P>
<P>
To further expand domestic demand, a vital task is to increase
income and consumption among low-income residents, he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
