<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur, EU Agree on Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 28 (Xinhua)-- The South American Common
Market (Mercosur) and the European Union (EU) agreed on Monday to
start negotiations in November on establishing a free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
The commitment was made during a meeting between the heads of
State or government of Mercosur (made up of Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay), Chile and EU countries, except Britain.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique, the parties said they will define in
next November the structure, methodology and calendar of
negotiations for a progressive free trade.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur and the EU said that negotiations will be carried out
without excluding any sector and in conformity with the rules of
the World Organization of Trade (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The parties said that the development of free trade between
Mercosur, Chile and the EU will invigorate their relations and
strengthen the multilateral trade system.
</P>
<P>
Both blocs envisage an establishment of a free trade zone by
the year 2004 or 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
