<HEADLINE> Croatia Appeals for WB Loans to Clear Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Croatia on Monday urged the World
Bank to provide it with loans for the clearance of more than one
million landmines deployed in the country during the civil war in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Jaranka Kosor, deputy speaker of the Croatian Parliament, made
the appeal in a speech to an international meeting on landmines
which opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kosor said Croatia needs some two billion dollars to clear all
landmines used in the civil war which erupted following the
disintegration of the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
She said that Croatia, a signatory to the international
convention forbidding the use, production, transport and storage
of landmines, has asked the World Bank to grant it loans for the
clearance of landmines laid in an area of 6,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Croatia, which has received 1.5 million dollars in aid from
Canada and the United States for the removal of landmines,
destroyed 3,500 landmines on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The international meeting was attended by representatives from
10 European countries, Canada and Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
