<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Booming in Batam, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign capital investment in
Indonesia's Batam island has amounted 13.5 million U.S. dollars
since the beginning of this year, boosted by the June 7 general
election.
</P>
<P>
"In this month of June four foreign companies have invested 1.5
million dollars, bringing the total number of foreign investment
companies in Batam in the January-June period to 18," Batam
authority's capital investment division chief Bachrudin Amir said
in Batam Monday.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that by the end of 1999 another 50 investors from
Singapore, the United States, Switzerland, Malaysia, Britain,
Canada, Norway, Japan and other countries are expected to invest
in Batam.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike the situation in the previous year, now foreign
investors consider Batam as a safe place for investment thanks to
the low inflation rate and the depreciation of the U.S. dollar,"
Antara News Agency Tuesday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
As an industrial zone, Batam has a competitive edge because of
its close proximity to Singapore and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Investment in Batam up till now and including 1998 stood at 7
billion dollars from 350 companies, 77 percent of which are
private investment, and 23 percent government investment.
</P>
<P>
During that period there had been 56 additional projects worth
a total of 108 million dollars. The keen interest of foreign
investors in doing business in Batam, Bachrudin said, was not only
due to the fact that it is a relatively safe place but also
because of its numerous facilities, which make it highly
competitive against Vietnam and other countries.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is God's gift to place Batam in such a strategic
location compared to its competitors in Asia," he added.
</P>
<P>
Not only are wages relatively low in Batam, the authorities
also exempt machinery and raw materials from import duties and
provide sales tax exemption and tax holidays for pioneer
industries.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Chief of the Batam Authority Ismeth Abdullah said
no foreign investor had left Batam after the onset of the economic
crisis in the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
To date there are 350 foreign companies operating in Batam,
employing about 160,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
Batam is also one of Indonesia's main tourist destinations
besides Jakarta and Bali, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, more than 1.2 million foreign tourists visited Batam,
up by 4.8 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
