<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dokic Keeps Dream Alive at Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Australian qualifier Jelena Dokic
kept her dream alive in Grand Slam with a straight set victory
over Mary Pierce of France on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ranked 129th and competing in only her third Grand Slam, Dokic,
at 16, sent her second top seed packing by defeating the ninth
seed rival 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Only five matches of the scheduled 16 were completed before
play was called off at 1830 GMT as rain swept across the All
England Club.
</P>
<P>
The women's quarter-finals were due to take place on Tuesday
but only 16-year-old qualifier Jelena Dokic, third seed Lindsay
Davenport and defending champion Jana Novotna have sealed their
places in the last eight. Organisers face a problem trying to fit
the 11 remaining fourth round games into the programme.
</P>
<P>
Dokic, the Australian sensation who toppled women's top seed
Martina Hingis in the first round, now plays either Lisa Raymond
or her compatriot Alexandra Stevenson, also a qualifier.
</P>
<P>
Only two other qualifiers have reached the women's quarter-
finals before at Wimbledon, the last being Molly van Nostrand of
the U.S.in 1985, and a semifinal place is now firmly in Dokic's
sights.
</P>
<P>
Novotna used her wealth of grass court experience to outplay
Nathalie Dechy of France 6-3, 7-5 on Monday and book a match with
Davenport, but it was a struggle all the way.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, the third seed, had the rain to thank as she
dispatched 14th seed Barbara Schett 7-6, 6-1. The match was
stopped for 70 minutes with the American 3-5, 0-30 down, and after
the break the Austrian lost her momentum.
</P>
<P>
Davenport saved six set points in the first set before taking
the tiebreak 9-7.
</P>
<P>
In the men's draw, fourth seed Andre Agassi of the United
States faced a serious test before he defeated Australian
qualifier Wayne Arthurs 6-7, 7-6, 6-1, 6-4 and earn a place in the
quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Agassi now plays Gustavo Kuerten, the Brazilian 11th seed who
had never won a match on grass before the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten beat Swiss qualifier Lorenzo Manta of Switzerland, a
man who had not won a match on the senior men's tour before
Wimbledon '99, 7-5, 6-4, 5-7, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
When the play was suspended, second women's seed Steffi Graf
was a set and 4-2 up against Belgian qualifier Kim Clijsters while
local hero and sixth seed Tim Henman was leading American Jim
Courier by two sets to one and 4-3.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia's Karol Kucera was two sets to one down against French
Cedric Pioline, the losing men's finalist in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Team Captain Cleared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- English premier league football
club Manchester United's championship winning captain Roy Keane
will not be prosecuted over an alleged assault on a woman in a
wine bar.
</P>
<P>
Keane, 27, was arrested by Greater Manchester Police on 17 May
after a woman accused him of assaulting her in Henry's Bar in the
city centre.
</P>
<P>
Leanne Carey told a tabloid newspaper Keane, who is also
captain of the Republic of Ireland's team, had kicked her in the
thigh after pouring a pint of beer over her friend.
</P>
<P>
But a rival newspaper later reported that Keane had been "
minding his own business" when a group of women approached and
threw a glass at him.
</P>
<P>
Keane was out with United team-mates David Beckham, Gary
Neville, Dwight Yorke and Andy Cole celebrating United's
Premiership title win 48 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
A Greater Manchester Police spokesman said: "Following a full
investigation, a file of evidence in relation to this matter was
submitted to the Crown Prosecution Service on 23 June.
</P>
<P>
"The written advice has now been received from the CPS and
following full consideration of all the facts, no further action
will be taken by Greater Manchester Police relating to the
aforementioned incident."
</P>
<P>
Keane's lawyer, Mike Kennedy, said: "We are happy with the
decision, it is the right decision."
</P>
<P>
Keane has worked hard in recent seasons to curb his notoriously
hot temper on the pitch.
</P>
<P>
He is hero worshipped by many Manchester United fans and his
absence, through injury, from most of the 1997/8 season is widely
considered to be the reason United lost out to Arsenal in both the
Championship and FA Cup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
