<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, June 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Monday announced its first
steps to reestablish the non-existent judicial system and began to
deploy the first team of international police to the field.
</P>
<P>
The steps are among the world body's continuous efforts to
defuse tensions between ethnic Serb and Albanian communities in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
(UN-Kosovo-Judiciary)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Rio de Janeiro -- The Southern Common Market (Mercosur) and the
European Union (EU) agreed here Monday to the start of
negotiations on a global free trade in November.
</P>
<P>
The commitment was made during a meeting between the heads of
state or government of Mercosur (made up by Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay), and Chile and the EU's 15 countries, except
Britain. In a joint communique, the parties said they will define
next November the structure, methodology and calendar of
negotiations for a progressive free trade. (Mercosur-EU-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- German police have been placed on alert for possible
outbreaks of violence by Kurdish groups in Germany after Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) leader Abdullah Ocalan is to be sentenced
Tuesday in Ankara, Media here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
But German Interior Minister Otto Schily said security
specialists expected no recurrence of the violence after Ocalan's
arrest, which caused waves of demonstrations by Kurds in the
capital cities of Europe. (Germany-Police-Ocalan)
</P>
