<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers for Trade Meet in Auckland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Trade ministers or
their representatives of all 21 economies of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) are gathering in Auckland, the biggest
city of New Zealand, for a two-day meeting to address key trade
issues facing APEC.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is regarded as an important preparation for the
informal meeting of APEC leaders to be held here in September.
</P>
<P>
The participants include Australian Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister for Trade Timothy Fischer, Thai Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Commerce Supachai Panitchpakdi and Japanese Minister
of International Trade and Industry Kaoru Yosano.
</P>
<P>
China's Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
Long Yongtu and the Chinese delegation headed by him are attending
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss issues on expanding opportunities for
business throughout the region, strengthening the functioning of
markets, improving coordination and focus in economic and
technical cooperation, broadening support for APEC.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Minister for International Trade Lockwood Smith
presided over the meeting and made opening remarks at the opening
session. He expressed the hope that the delegates from various
countries and regions would have a free and open dialogue on the
issues and make substantial progress at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
