<HEADLINE> Italy's Ruling Center-left Coalition Wins Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Ruling Center-left coalition
won the Italy's local administrative elections which were held in
66 provinces and 28 provincial capitals in two rounds last Sunday
and June 13, but conceding the traditional bastion of the left,
Italian central city of Bologna, and Italian north province of
Milan to the opposing Center-right.
</P>
<P>
According to the final result unveiled by Italian news agency
of ANSA Monday, among the 66 provinces up for renewal in the
contests opening June 13, 46 went to the Center-left and 20 to the
Center-right, a line-up which compares to 55 held by the
Center-left before the vote, seven by the Center-right and four by
the North League.
</P>
<P>
In the 28 provincial capitals, 19 wound up in Center-left hands
and nine with the Center-right, compared to 24 in the Center-left
camp on the eve of the elections and four held by the
Center-right.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema recognized Monday in Rio
de Janeiro of Brazil that the Center-left's defeat in Bologna
after more than fifty years of left-wing or center-left rule was
"grave and painful".
</P>
<P>
But, talking to reporters before the opening of the summit of
EU and Latin American leaders there, he pointed out that, despite
the Center-left losses in provincial and city elections,
Center-left administrations remain "prevalent by a large margin"
in local government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
