<DOCNO> XIE19990629.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Studies on China's Internet Market Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ENGELES, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China's Internet user base will
exceed 33 million by 2003, growing at an annual rate of nearly 60
percent over the next five years, a U.S. market research firm reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Chinese Internet users will climb from 2.1 million last
year to more than 6.7 million, according to the Strategis Group, which
has recently conducted a study jointly with BDA (China) Limited, the
leading Internet and telecom market strategy firm in China.
</P>
<P>
The two firms suggest that China is already the fastest growing
Internet market in Asia and will become one of the world's leading
markets in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
With more than 33 million users by 2003, according to the joint
study, each new user that comes online creates new opportunities for
Internet-related business, enabling companies to leverage their
technology, service or capital in "one of the world's most exciting
Internet markets."
</P>
<P>
China's market for Internet service providers (ISP) is experiencing
"survival of the fattest," the Strategis Group said. Those ISPs,
typically owned or funded by China Telecom, with access to the fattest
pipes such as dial-up lines, leased lines and Internet bandwidth, have
emerged on top. Nevertheless, opportunities are growing for new
players, including cable TV operators, to tap revenues in the ISP
market, which are forecast to exceed 4 billion U.S. dollars by 2003.
</P>
<P>
China also presents a burgeoning market opportunity for Internet
equipment, software and service. This sector is expected to exceed 160
million U.S. dollars in 1999. Foreign vendors currently dominate
China's Internet infrastructure market, but domestic players are
expanding their efforts to serve this growing market, said the
Strategis Group.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released early this year by China Internet
Network Information Center (CINIC), the number of Internet users in
China has been growing at an annual rate of over 100 percent. The
center's more conservative estimation is that the users will surpass
six million by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
